Text: I am praying to the kami for luck since I am about to leave on a treasure hunt. Would you like to join me?
One wrong move and you will have the pleasure of being acquainted with my lance.
...We have naught to discuss. Nor have you aught to discuss with Isobe, I should think. Therefore you have no reason to remain.
Has something happened at Shisui of the Violet Tides? Rarely are we kept informed of the ongoings of the castle. I mean, none of us even know what our own ruler, the Ruby Princess, looks like!
Hey, missmister, what is the surface like? Is it a nice place? Or is it scary? Do you have seaweed that grows up to the skies? Or do you have...
If I may ask, what brings you to our humble village, madamsir? It is not every day that we receive visitors from the surface.

The Kojin of the Red have become even more aggressive of late. It has caused our people no end of trouble. <sigh> If only they were a bit more like their amicable cousins in Tamamizu, perhaps we would not have to suffer so...
It is my dream to one day meet the Ruby Princess. I bet she is beautiful! Have you ever met her, missmister?
I am currently in the middle of delegating fishing tasks. Unless what you have to say is of great import, pray come and find me later.
Oh, dear... <sigh> What have my sons done this time?
I could have sworn there were at least two fish left on this line. Did someone sneak off with them?
Ah, there is nothing better than having a smoke after a long day of fishing...
Selling all of this should earn me enough money to make it through to the next moon.
Nothing can compare to the seas' magnificence. Standing here and looking upon their beauty always helps me clear my thoughts.
While many of us prefer the taste of fresh fish, we must preserve most of what we catch for days our hauls are not so bountiful.
This meager haul will fetch us but a pouchful of coins at the market. <sigh> It seems every day the number of fish we catch dwindles. We really must look into finding new fishing grounds.
Quiet. Do not break my concentration. The very clothes on my back ride on the outcome of this game.
I do not know how I am going to carry all of this to the marketplace on my own...
I am about to set out on a fishing voyage and am inspecting my boat to make sure everything is in working order.
The both of us were born and bred in Isari, which is presumably why the chief has stationed us here. It is good to be home for a time.
I am looking to make a rod that will not put any strain on my back. My friend is in the middle of testing my latest design for me.
While the Coral Banquet is primarily a lookout post, occasionally we will also conduct rituals here to ensure the safe return of those going out to sea.

From here we survey the northern expanse of ocean. Most enemy fleets will approach our island from these waters, and it is for this reason alone that the Coral Banquet is considered to be the Confederacy's most dangerous post.
Please, madamsir, do not break my concentration. Were enemy troops to approach and I failed to raise the alarum, the deaths of my fellow Confederates will be on my hands.

There is a real technique to this. You cannot just go spreading fertilizer anywhere. You must take account of the different types of rice plant and their individual needs. It is a lot like raising children really.
They say persimmons taste better the longer you stare at them. This one is going to be positively delicious.
Namai may seem like a peaceful village, but believe me, we have had our share of troubles. Too many to count.
I would love nothing more than to devour an entire tiger right now.
The Empire said I was too sickly to fight for them. I was glad to avoid conscription at first, but my joy was short-lived when I realized they had taken all of my closest friends.
All of my closest friends have been conscripted into the imperial army. I spend most of my days now just watching my daughter over there playing. She is all I have left.
We have suffered a great deal, but when I gaze upon these flowers, I am able to forget all our troubles. If only for a moment.
Have you already taken in our paddies? We raise them as if they were our children. They are a rare source of happiness for me in these dark times.
Agh, all this labor is not helping my poor old back.
Ah, I see you there. Admiring my bamboo pole collection, were you not? Always nice to meet a fellow enthusiast. It has taken me a not-insignificant amount of time to amass all of these.
So much rice, so little time.
I knew Lord Hien only by name and reputation until today. There is no denying that he has a presence...
In the midst of training I was, my body aflame, my garments soaked through with sweat, when these kindred spirits begged leave to train together! You are welcome to join us too, my friend!
While you were away, others came unto us, eager to pledge themselves to the cause. Namai was only the beginning...
Lord Hien has returned! Lord Hien has returned! And together we will drive the imperials out of Doma once and for all!
I have tried to hone my skills in preparation for this day. I have no burning desire to spill blood, but if I must...then so be it.
Used to be I couldn't imagine it being any better, but now I can see it. One day someone will ask me who I am, and I will tell them I am Isse of Doma, not with shame...but with pride.
But I know we can't do it alone, so I hope...I hope you'll continue to help us. Please.
The Drunken Toad was made using parts from an old riverboat. It carried rice used to make alcohol up and down the river─that's where the name comes from.
You needn't worry for your safety within these walls. No, no. The Namazu here are civilized─we would never attack man.
You are aware that we Namazu can read and write, yes? Quite literate, quite smart. And I have the finest writing of all here in Yuzuka Manor. I just wanted to share that with you.
All of the Namazu here are quite civilized. Very dignified, very sophisticated. The bells you see at our necks are proof enough of that.
You are an accomplished and traveled womanman of the world. Yes, yes. I wish very much to be like you one day.
We were just discussing what might make a good gift for the people of Namai. I believe a vase would do quite nicely, yes, yes.
Those fools are off hiding again drowning themselves in tea. And after I've told them so many times not to. All Namazu know that stuff is for drunkards and mummers.
This must seem like a sad place to an outsider. It used to be quite lively before half of the blasted village was conscripted into the Empire's army.
This area's water comes from the Heron's Flight. Truly, I have not seen a cleaner waterfall in my life. I am ever thankful as it nurtures the fish my husband and I use to trade for rice.
Abandoning my post? I'll have you know I'm more than capable of keeping watch and fishing at the same time!
Hmm yes, it seems there is indeed some water leaking from these rocks.
When the Empire came, I begged them to take me instead of the young ones.
I miss Geser terribly, but I know I need only be patient. He will return─I am sure of it.
Have you business with me? No? Then away with you!
Every day with my boy brings new discoveries. He reminds me of the man he was in many ways, but in others he is much different...
It may take many years and much work, but I will become the warrior I once was!
This is more than just a game. This is war!
Do not disturb me. I must be ever vigilant.
It is neither easy nor enjoyable work, but someone needs to keep a record of our supplies.
We are worthy of neither Azim nor Nhaama's protection. We do not even deserve this fire that keeps us warm.
I did not ask for the title of udgan and I do not enjoy holding it.
Those who cling to such concepts are doomed to walk a path of greed. Our tribe will not make that same mistake again.

These murals tell stories of our ancestors' greed. Whenever our tribe gains something, we make sure to look upon these walls, that we do not fall victim to the same temptations as those who came before us.
This seems to be the Qestir tribe's khan. He welcomes you to Reunion with a smile.
Khaishan eyes you with suspicion. It seems he is wary of you bringing harm to Iturgen.
Cotota meets your gaze for a second before looking away shyly.
The Qestir believe all words are merely lies. That is why they do not speak.
It is also why I am forced to deal with so many troubled travelers, unable to understand Reunion's ways. I do not enjoy the role, but there are few others here willing to explain things orally.
The glint of confusion in Beki's eyes suggests she is not entirely sure why you have come up here.
I have many goods from far beyond the borders of the Steppe. Mayhap they are common trinkets to you, traveler...but should you desire the familiar, you need only ask!
Why, that exotic aura you emit... You must be a traveler from far-off lands! Can I interest you in some kumis?
I came here to sell my wool, but no one seems interested. I suppose the only tribes who would be are those that live to the north.
Tell me, as a fellow outsider, what do you think of Qestiri customs? They are a bit of an odd bunch if you ask me, but at least they are willing to let non-Xaela trade here as well.
Travelers from without are always welcome! Travelers with a taste for organs and coin to pay, that is!
Many plants found on the Steppe may be used in medicines and poisons. To a traveler, it may be difficult to discern the difference. Safer to buy what you seek from me.
Buuz! Fresh buuz! Guaranteed to satisfy! Made with game caught daily by the finest Dazkar hunters, and prepared by our husbands! Fresh buuz!
One must remember to reward their beasts of burden for their service. Were it not for her, I could not have crossed the northern mountains, nor brought so much to market.
All tribal rivalries are to be forgotten while one is in Reunion. That is the principle the marketplace was founded on. I truly hope the day comes when we are all at peace.
All tribes may come and go freely from Reunion. Those who we consider friend...and those who we do not.
Vexing, perhaps, but such is the law. Few are so foolish as to break the peace, so precious is this place.
One never knows when they might be attacked on the Steppe. As a result, I have to keep watch all day and night. The rare times when I do sleep, I do so up here.
All is in accordance with their design. Mol Iloh is your home.
I would caution you to comport yourself with dignity in the presence of Temulun Khatun...but I sense that will not be necessary.
The gods said I should cook steak today, but they neglected to say if it should be rare, medium, or well-done...
We all have our own roles to play to keep order in our tribe. That is why I trade.
She is lovely, is she not? The gods told me to feed her until she grew nice and plump.
Apologies, but I can spare no time for you. Once I have finished taking stock of these supplies, I must spend time with the children.
I feel such a strong connection to my darling sheep. I have even given them all names. Would you like to hear them?
The other day the gods told me to tell a friend, one I had been fighting with, five things that I appreciate about them.

Unfortunately, I was unable to overcome my own pride to actually speak with my friend that day. However, I have since learned the importance of being humble. I decided to apologize to her and we are now once again on good terms!
Nothing relaxes me more than listening to someone playing the morin khuur. My mother often used to lull me to sleep with one when I was a child.
These sheep are the best family I have ever had.
My dreams of late have been haunted by images of my mild-mannered pup here devouring my flock. I cannot think why. He has never even growled at them.
Today's enemies are tomorrow's allies. Remember this.
Sheep are essential to our survival here on the Steppe, and it is my primary responsibility to take care of our flocks.
Beyond these doors is the throne room of our most radiant brother Magnai. You are to approach him with the utmost respect.
Do not be deceived by my frailty. I too am Oronir, and I once fought with the ferocity of my brothers. Now I serve the tribe in a different manner.
All those who live here in the Dawn Throne are extremely capable warriors. Many, however, have grown a little too confident in their abilities and might need to be brought down a peg or two.

Regardless of the heavy rains or winds that sweep through these areas, the flames of these torches shall always burn bright, here in the Dawn Throne, where the first children of Father Azim were ushered into this world.
What business brings you to the Dawn Throne? Answer wisely.

While being so high up makes it almost impossible for enemy forces or wild animals to attack us, it does come at a price. We must regularly herd our sheep to the fields below and back. Trust me when I say it is not nearly so easy as it sounds.
I have no use for you.
Do not even think to sneak even a spoonful of our food. We barely have enough rations to feed our own people. We cannot afford to provide for all the hungry mouths that pass through here.
I am observing the movements of the Dotharl. After all, they have launched a countless number of assaults on us in the past.
While I will not deny that there are many disputes between our tribes, we somehow always manage to resolve them. Allying ourselves with the Oronir was the best thing we could have done.
Please, move away from the sheep! Can you not see you are disturbing them?
...We have naught to discuss, woman.Hmm... Yes...yes... This one is special.

Have care, my friend. The area beyond is fraught with danger.
...Well? I'd wager that served to awaken the explorer within you.
I've been watching these two play for a while now, but the rules don't make much sense to me. Much more of a Triple Triad man myself. Do you fancy a match?
Zenos may be dead, and the XIIth defeated, but the Empire's not going anywhere. Ala Mhigo still needs the Resistance.
My father used to say that freedom is just an opportunity. A chance to build something better. Well, now that we've got it, it's up to us what comes next.
The children are away tending to the herds. When they learn you were here, they will doubtless shed tears of sadness, for you are well-liked.

It is all too easy to lose sight of our place within the grand scheme of things. That is why I traveled the world, pen in hand, and endeavored to record the events I saw. Even now, my habits remain─whenever I find a few moments to myself, I write.
There's never enough of anything to go around, which is why they put a man like me in charge of the stores. Some folks have trouble saying no. I don't.
Fassster! Fassster! Be quick or be dead! The imperials will show you no mercy!
The path ahead leads to the Temple of the Fist, and it is my duty to ensure that only those of sound body and mind are permitted to pass.
We have been trying to concoct a potion using only materials easily found in Gyr Abania, but it is proving to be anything but a simple task.
Our fighters never know when they'll be able to take a meal. All I can do is try to make sure that when they do, they'll have something to look forward to.
Moaning about our dearth of supplies isn't going to change anything. It is up to me to find some way of replenishing our stocks or people's lives may be at risk.
If you're looking for the tunnel to the Peaks, it's right this way.
I have been told to destroy the aetheryte should the imperial army find its way here. Though I truly hope it does not come to that.
Ours is a cause that knows no boundaries. Ala Mhigan, Ananta─all are welcome in the fight for freedom!
Not bad, eh? These bastards'll turn magitek armor to scrap in the blink of an eye!
The Vira have no love for the imperials. Full glad are we to pledge our blades to the Resissstance.
Do watch yourself around these chocobos. They're trained for combat so they're a bit more aggressive than your average bird.
Too many wounded, too little medicine, too much to worry about. So I don't. Instead, I pray every day for the fighting to end.
I fear there may not be much I can do for this man...
You wouldn't believe how many bandages we go through in a day. I pray we get more soon...
Bastards got me in the shoulder... I've still the strength to stand on a battlefield, but I'm no good to anyone like this...
You learn to live off the land when you're in the Resistance. You'd be surprised what herbs people carelessly trample underfoot.
This is the Barber. You'll find countless injured fighters here either undergoing treatment or awaiting it. Tread softly should you go inside.
There is much to be learned from the magitek weapons left by the Garleans along Baelsar's Wall. If all goes as planned, we will soon turn their own technology against them.

I'd be careful out there if I were you. A womanman your size─the beasts out there would swallow you whole. And you wouldn't be the first, either.There are beasts out there big enough to swallow a man whole. Well, a man my size, at least.
It's been far too long since the four great nations of Eorzea fought together under a single banner. Soon the Garleans will learn the folly of encroaching on our lands.
It's been no easy task distributing provisions with so many soldiers. I shudder to think what would happen should our supply lines be cut off. There's barely enough to go around as it is.
I've been so anxious to do battle with the Garleans, I sometimes find myself tightly gripping the hilt of my blade without realizing it. Perhaps that is to blame for the blisters on my hand.
We recently seized a suit of magitek armor from Baelsar's Wall. Until we've completed its examination, civilians are not permitted inside─not even adventurers.
It will not be easy, but we must do all we can to reverse the damage done to the land here.
It's actually quite nice having this post to myself. A great view, and no one to spoil it.
This was simply called Velodyna bridge before the Garleans arrived. They saw fit to transform it into a base for their supply trains.
What's more, atop this tower they could survey the area for malms around. Their ambition knows no bounds, nor does their villainy.
The presence of imperials forced us to abandon much of our hunting grounds. With our resources diminished as they are, relations with the Ananta have proven invaluable to our survival.
Though it fills my heart with pride to know that my daughter is fighting for this noble cause, a part of me wants nothing more for her to come home.
That said, I know better than to try and stop her. So I wait and I hope and I pray...
The three of us have hunted together for as long as I can remember. When tracking our prey, it's as if we're of one mind.
The Garleans aren't the only thing we have to watch out for, you know. Why, some flyin' abomination could swoop down and snatch you up just like that.
These two will make fine hunters someday. But first, they'll need to improve their marksmanship.
The Lady of Blisss embodies freedom─that which the imperials would take from usss. As her children, there is but one path: to fight, and to fight, and to fight.
We make great effortsss to preserve not only our own beauty, but that of our home. That is why we asssk those who visit Vira Nilya take care not to make a messs.
It ssstill amazes me how you striders maintain your posssture atop those stumps you call legsss.
I've been told there are fanaticsss among your kind who covet our ssskin. Is that true? I underssstand they may envy our beauty, but that is sssimply revolting.

Is it not inconvenient to require a male to reproduce? What exactly do they... On sssecond thought, perhapsss I shouldn't ask.The females of your kind require a male to reproduce, correct? How exactly do you... On sssecond thought, perhapsss I shouldn't ask.
Our leader Sarisha has ever been one to sssee the good in others. Even now she sssends envoys to the Qalyana in the hopes of underssstanding their people.
I'll never underssstand why your kind needs fire to work metal when any number of magicksss can do so just as easily, if not more so.
<pant> There're beasties about what burrow underground an' lie in wait for prey. <pant> Gotta keep nimble, like, so as to not get caught by one. <grunt>
Hatred leads to war, war incites revenge, and revenge breeds hatred. It is a vicious cycle I pray we someday break. But it is hard in the face of the ruin brought upon us by the Garleans.
The Qalyana are sssuch cowards. Our sisters continue to be ssslain and yet they refuse to draw their bladesss. The world crumblesss around them, and all they care for is their gemcraft.
Every time I close my eyes, I see their faces. Their wild eyes, their hungry smiles...
When the quarry stopped providin' for us we decided to build our homes in it instead. I've seen a crack or two appear in my walls lately, but I'd still put money on this house outliving me!
When my sister first went to work at Byron's Bread I had hoped she might be able to share some of their harvest with me. Alas, it does not seem like they produce much in the first place.
All of my friends left the village quite some time ago. I would be lying if I said I hadn't considered joining them, but had I gone as well, there would be hardly any young people remaining.
As I'm too weak to do any hard labor, Raganfrid tasked me with managing village affairs. It's not the most enjoyable work, but then there's little enjoyable about Ala Gannha in the first place.
This here's the leftovers. Dust and gravel and the like. Us too, you might say. We've shaped the Peaks, and they've shaped us in turn.
My brother over there is on the lookout for nasty people. Not really sure what he plans to do if one does happen to appear.
We still receive orders for stone now and then. Though they're so few in number I can more than handle them all myself.

Cooking up a tasty stew to fuel our friend quarrying over there. I'd help him by taking up a pickaxe myself, but we'd end up with more stone than we could ever sell. There just isn't that much demand for it nowadays.
There's no poetry in this work. No fulfillment of a job well done. You do it cause you've got no choice, and that's that.
Oh, my poor back. I spend every waking hour working these rocky fields and for what? One of the most pathetic harvests I have ever seen.
There must be some use I can find for this pile of hay...
I do hope you haven't come looking to buy crops. 'Fraid we've nothing to sell at the moment.
Now that those damned imperial dogs are gone, we can get to rebuildin' and make Ala Ghiri a real tradin' center like it used to be.

I'll admit I did less-than-honorable things to make my fair share of profits when the Garleans were here. I'm a merchant, after all. That said, I plan to use my savings to get this place on its feet again. Just a matter of how...
If you ever need a drink, stop by my pub any time you like for one on the house. Any friend of the Resistance is a friend of mine.

At last, Ala Ghiri is free to become the trading center of Gyr Abania once more. And more trade means more profits! All of those deliveries for the Resistance without compensation are finally paying off.
Sorry, misssir, but you'll have to move along. I'm meetin' someone regardin' a rather urgent matter, and they should be here any moment.
That crystal up there's a beauty, isn't it? Only thing that could improve the view is a nice, cold bottle of arak.
If there's something you need, I'd suggest speaking with officer Brazen Brook. Things tend to go much more smoothly when he's involved.

The people of Ala Ghiri will be safe so long as our men keep in line, but for the moment we're still only a pack of faceless soldiers to them. If we don't do all we can to make things better here, we're no better than the Garlean bastards who were here before us.
No need to be concerned of enemy movement to the north. If anything moves even an ilm out there, we'll see it.
Times are changing, and with change comes opportunity for business. It's only a matter of finding that special something to catch the customer's eye.
Have you seen any trees in need of attention? Sagging boughs? Rotting roots?
Anything you need? Give me a hand with my stock, and I'll see about lowering my prices.
Ah! Oh gods, please don't do that. I thought the Empire's soldiers had come for me...
I'm afraid we've nothin' to offer you, misssir. Barely anythin' grows here, and most of our able-bodied men and women either fled or were conscripted. I reckon this place only has a few years left...
Raubahn was the one what led the armies to free Ala Mhigo? My, he's grown to be quite the soldier, hasn't he?
Ma said all the Garlean people ran away. Pa will be so happy when he comes home. He's been gone an awfully long time, though. I hope he's okay...
These crates are─or rather, were─filled with food. I thought it'd last longer, but it looks like we're nearly out. I pray we have enough to buy more.
Hm? Weren't you going to do something about the shellbacks?
Well then. I can only assume your affairs in Yanxia were not as pressing as I thought.

Or were you worried about us? Don't be. We've had some skirmishes with the imperials since Isari, but we've managed to hold our own. This state of affairs cannot be sustained indefinitely, of course...so I would ask that you hurry.
The Confederacy is of a thousand nations and of none. I, for example, was born in a fishing village, whereas this one hails from the plains of Yanxia. His stories never cease to entertain!
This sekibune may be past her prime, but that gives her all the more character, I say! A pity she so rarely sees combat.
Alas, none can deny that a flotilla of smaller ships is more effective in most cases. Easier to trap a larger vessel and less danger to us all should they be armed.
Never underestimate the importance of guard duty, I say. If one truly values his freedom, he must be ever ready to defend it.
If you refuse to pay the Ruby Tithe, we will strip you of everything you have─including the very clothes on your back! Gahaha!
Aye, I'm a pirate and aye, I'm a cook. And a good one at that! I know the best seasoning for any dish: plenty of drink to wash it down!
By the look of it, our new recruits have, once again, charged into a head-to-head battle with some deadly sea beasts. Those fools never learn, do they?
Ahhh, is there aught in this world finer than strong spirits and tobacco? I think not... <hic> Hm? What is it? A game of chance? Another time, perhaps... <hic>
This is a much safer place for lookouts to be stationed than the Coral Banquet. That is why most new recruits start here.
If you set your net according to the position of the moon and rhythm of the tide, it won't take long for it to become full. Most days I can catch enough food to feed our entire crew.
We help clean ships and fix nets. When Mister Tsukikage deems our work done, then we go off to play!
The past holds no power over us. What you are is what you do now and ever after. Such is the way of the Confederacy.

As you can imagine, many of the men and women here have rather murky pasts. While what they have done in their former lives is of no concern to us, any who break Confederate law will have to answer to me.
It is not uncommon for us to find ourselves under attack. That is why we have heightened the security in this area and carefully monitor all activity in the waters surrounding our island.
Turn around and go back whence you came. This is a restricted area.
I suppose I could try dragging this stone along the ground if no one comes to help me...
I've not even done much today and I'm already knackered. Some days this village just saps the life out of me.
Ah, the old joints aren't what they used to be. I can hardly believe I used to go up and down these slopes with ponzes of stone in hand.
We're all equal in the eyes of M'rahz Nunh. His fair-mindedness is part of what makes him so well loved among our people.

That settlement down there in the distance is the Qalyana tribe of the Ananta. For one reason or another they've chosen to keep out of the fighting. Even when their fellow Ananta from the other tribes come under attack they do nothing. Strange, isn't it?
The fires of war spread across Gyr Abania, and soon we ourselves may be forced to enter the fray.
Should it come to pass, then it will fall to me to guide my people through the flames, for I have the rare and unfortunate honor to serve not only as nunh, but as leader of my people.
Aye, this one can't fail! I can feel my purse growing heavier already...
There are broken warmachina all over the place if you know where to look. Someone should probably salvage them...
Leave me be. I just need a moment or two, then I'll get back to work...

Even a woman in my profession has standards, you know. The imperials were nothing but brutes and pigs. You, and the good men and women of the Resistance, on the other hand, are more than welcome to partake of my services.

You'll find there are quite a number of taverns and inns here in Ala Ghiri. After all, this was originally a trading hub. The Garleans saw little need for trade, however, and used our village only for drink and debauchery. Good riddance, I say.
I'm glad to be rid o' those godsdamned imperials. Maybe now we can finally get back to tradin' like the good ol' days.

This beauty of a bird has been leading our caravans, transporting all manner of provisions for the soldiers here in Ala Ghiri. Now that we've arrived, she'll have plenty of rest and all the gysahl greens she can eat.

I'm thankful for all the Resistance has done, but I still worry for the future. We've lost so many over the years, and if the Garleans should ever return... No, I don't think it's time to celebrate just yet.
It's not easy keeping watch out here with only Guntmar to keep me company. But if we don't do it, I'm afraid no one else will.
I just finished slaughtering these two lambs for their wool and meat. Their bleating yet fills my ears. Unlike we Dotharl, they shall never be reborn.
Look at them. So full of vigor. Few things bring me more pleasure than seeing my sheep happy.
You wish to train with us? It will not be easy. We live to do battle.
I must get home quickly and feed my little brother and sister. But not quite yet. I must hand out just a few missives more.
Absolutely beautiful. Would you not agree?
It is not easy living in these caves. When the fire fades, you cannot even make out your own hands in the darkness.
However, this is the life our tribe deserves. We must never be tempted by greed again.

I'll have you know that in all of Yuzuka Manor, none is more knowledgeable about the value of things than I. Nobody, no one. If you wish to gauge the worth of something, you need only come and show it to me. Yes, yes.
I'd only ever heard tell of Ala Mhigo in the reports─it is a far grander city than I expected.
I have traveled here from distant Coerthas to support the efforts of the Alliance. Pray call upon me should you have need of a chirurgeon's skills.
They say merchant caravans once used this juncture as a waypoint before setting off from Ala Mhigo to other lands. I hope to see it returned to such a use one day...
My poor chocobos are exhausted. I should organize the wagon while they rest...
To see Ala Mhigo right in front of us like this... Aye, it makes the pulse quicken!
It was an honor to meet you, GCRankLimsaMaleTextGCRankGridaniaMaleTextGCRankUldahMaleText  !
Don't you worry, madamsir! We'll make sure the supplies are in order!
Have you familiarized yourself with the lay of the land, madamsir? There are a number of structures and formations we need to see secured...
This place is a bit too dusty for my taste. I find myself missing the forest...
The smell of saltwater in the air here reminds me of home. I find it quite comforting.
Ssso, thisss is Ala Mhigo. These ssstrider cities are all edges and corners─they lack elegance.

I say, weren't you one of the ones who was with my grandson Wiscar? I knew I recognized you. My heartfelt thanks, lasslad, for liberating our homeland. I didn't think the day would come, leastwise not within my lifetime.

To be sure, there's still much and more work to do before Ala Mhigo can know her former glory, but together we'll rebuild her, one block at a time. Young ones like you and Wiscar have already put in the hardest yalms; it's time for this old fossil to put in some of his own!
Livin's hard enough as it is...
I do wonder just what will become of us. We have been under imperial rule for over two decades. What are we supposed to do now?
There is still much work to be done, but I'm prepared to do whatever it takes to get Ala Mhigo back on its feet.
Go and bother someone else.
I know what you're thinking: a defenseless Garlean rat, just my luck! But please, resist the urge to cut me open and trample my entrails! I did not choose to enlist!
I too want nothing more than to flee from here, but I cannot find my way out─it's like a blasted maze!

You seem a decent sort, and I would love nothing more than to tell you about a number of profitable ventures...but I'm not at liberty to do so without the express permission of Geimlona in Idyllshire.
At Aunt Rowena's behest, I've brought the House of Splendors to Rhalgr's Reach. We hope to rely on your continued support!
My apologies, but I can only accept scrips from individuals who stand in good stead with the House.
If you have scrips you wish to spend, I would be happy to assist you.
Forgive me, but we are not allowed to do business with just anyone. You must be known to the House first.
Ah, MistressMaster  , always a pleasure. Please feel free to browse our selection of tools and gear.
As much as I would like to assist you, I'm permitted to do business only with referred individuals.
If you have scrips with you, I'd be glad to take them off your hands in exchange for an item of your choice.
Sorry, love, but I can only assist them as the House knows.
If ye got scrips, I got all sorts o' fine wares ye can exchange 'em fer.
I offer wares in exchange for scrips, but my services are available only to those whom the House knows and trust.
Good eveningmorrowdayevening to you, madamsir. If you are in possession of any scrips, I can offer you myriad useful wares in exchange for them.
Nice to see you again,  ! No problems to report here.
...You are certain that you are dry? Flesh and clothing both? Go and stand by a cookfire outside if any water remains.
You are returned from Bardam's Mettle...but alone? What of Hien and the others?
Brilliant. I'd been itching to play for a while now.
Sorry, I can't play right now. I need to see which one of these two is going to win.
Ah, that was quite enjoyable. It'd been a while since anyone here was brave enough to challenge me to a match. Better luck next time.
Even the best of champions lose sometimes. Let us play again in the near future. I expect you to give me a chance to reclaim my honor.
Ha ha! I have not enjoyed myself that much in a good while. I hope we have a chance to play again someday.
Triple...Triad? Oh yes, I remember now! A sailor once insisted that I accept some of the cards as a gift. I would be glad to play a match with you, but please do not expect much skill on my part.
My apologies, but I cannot play games while there are customers to be served.
Oh, I won? Well, that was rather enjoyable for a game I barely understand. We decided that the loser was to order a glass of junmaishu, did we not?
I am not sure why I lost, but it does not make losing any less frustrating. Gather your cards, madamsir, and we shall play another round!
A draw? Hm, I would prefer to play until the victor is clear. Another match!
Triple...<hic>...Triad, you say? Bahahaha! Very well! <hic> I have had enough to drink to indulge your request. Break out your cards and prepare to lose, my friend!
Ah, I would love nothing more than to join you for a round of cards, but now is not a good time. I must keep my eyes and ears peeled─there are traitors among us.
Don't worry. Few can best me at this game. You are always welcome to challenge me again─if you dare, that is! Bahahaha!
...You won? B-But how!? I never lose! Take your cards back out. We are playing another round.
A draw? You got lucky this time, friend. You, however, won't be so fortunate this next round.
Ah, I was hoping someone might come along and challenge me to a game! Well, what are you waiting for? Pull out your cards and let us begin!
Thank you for asking, but I am afraid I do not have the time for games right now. I would, however, be more than happy to play a round with you after I finish polishing this shell.
Haha! Victory is mine! No doubt it is the kami's way of thanking me for all my hard work!
I...lost? Kami, forgive me! I should never have dozed off while polishing our guardian spirit's shell! I promise it shan't ever happen again!
A draw? <sigh> It seems the kami favor neither one of us this day.
These cards can be used to play a game? I traded a barrel of fish for them in Namai! Yes, yes, I was told they were very precious, very rare.
My apologies, but I must tend to the flowers.
Victory is mine, yes, yes? And to think, I almost threw my cards away! I licked them, I did, and they did not taste as good as they looked...
You are as skillful in play as you are in battle! It must be dull to excel in everything, to always be showered in praise...
Difficult, difficult, this game is very difficult. But I am enjoying the learning of it, nonetheless! Let us play again, yes, yes?
I was in Reunion earlier and one of the merchants there gave me a rather interesting card. I would quite like to try it out. Could I interest you in a match?
I am sorry to turn you down, but the gods have given me other duties to attend to. Let us play again another time!
I am victorious! Just according the elder gods' plan.
I lost? Did the elder gods not send me to Reunion so I would be victorious? Perhaps they only wanted for me to enjoy a match with you. Yes, that must be it.
A draw! Quite a match indeed. Let us play again sometime.
You wish to challenge me─the undisputed champion of our tribe─to a game of Triple Triad? You are a daring womanman.
Forgive me, but I must tend to the sheep. Come back later and maybe we can play a round then.
Haha! Now do you see why I am the undisputed champion of the Oronir!?
You only won because I...I was distracted! Come, let us do it again!
It seems we have tied. Come challenge me again sometime that we might declare a true winner.
A match of Triple Triad? That is a fine idea. I only began playing a short while ago, but that will not hold me back.
I cannot play at this moment. Return later.
Let this be a lesson to you. Experience means naught if you lack the desire to win.
The taste of defeat is new to me. I will ensure this does not happen again.
You have taught me much. Next time I shall use this knowledge against you.
You wish to challenge me? ...To a game of cards? ...Right now? Well, I suppose it would not hurt to forget our troubles for a time.
It has been some time since last I played, but it seems I remember the strategies. I thank you for the pleasant distraction.
Strange. Though I lost the match, I still feel oddly satisfied.
I did not claim victory, but it was a good match, nonetheless. I'd almost forgotten how it felt to enjoy myself. Mayhap I should challenge some of the others to a game...
Ah yesss, Triple Triad. My sssisters fighting with the Resistance taught me this game. If you wish to challenge me, then let usss begin.
Sorry, but I have no time for games. I must be ready should my sssisters need me.
Hah! Are you sssurprised? You may see this as jussst a game, but we Ananta take all battlesss very seriously. Even Triple Triad.
How disssgraceful. What will the others think if they find out about this?
Hmmm. Perhapsss I've underestimated you. Care to play again? I won't hold back thisss time.
Please, before you kill me, let me play a game of Triple Triad!
You have a deck, do you not? Please, I beg you.
I cannot play at the moment. I am far too busy trying to keep my head attached to my body!
Feel it! Feel Garlemald's might! How foolish you were to think your rebellion could ever succeed.
Oh no. I-I didn't mean it, I swear! Please, spare me my life!
My darling chocobo awaits me back home. Do not make an orphan of her!
How dare you raise your hand against your imperial master? You are nothing more than rebel scum!
Ah, that is to say I am incredibly sorry! Do not butcher me! I still have so much to live for.
A draw? You have quite the nerve standing up to me. You do understand what this armor signifies, don't you?
But of course you do! I was an absolute fool to think otherwise. Please, do not skewer me before tearing me limb from limb! I am so very sorry!
I am sorry, but I have nothing to offer you. Come back again some other time.

If you wish to trade in Centurio Seals, then you'll first need Estrild's approval. A tall order, indeed, but surely not insurmountable for one who has stared death in the face once or thrice...

The Hounds'll show the rest of Ishgard that we lowborn can make a difference. I promise we'll devour every scrap of trainin' you care to throw our way!
How about that, eh? Our first big mission, and we recovered a sacred bloody sword. I'm still a bit curious about that firearm, but I'll let Rostnsthal deal with it for the now.
If there's aught wrong with that sword, Lord Stephanivien'll soon find it. And we'll be ready and waitin' to act when he does.
! The Hounds are trottin' along just fine thanks to you an' that ol' pirate.
I've even been workin' with Muscadain to coordinate our efforts with the Temple Knights. Afore long, it'll be as if the watch was always a part of the city─like we was one of them stones in the wall.
The Hounds of Ishgard, eh? Aye, I like the bloody sound of that! Let's get on with this training already!
What do you think of that, then,  ? Not bad for a motley lot of lowborn, I reckon! After a mission like that, we should have no trouble keeping the peace at the ceremony.

Now, I know I'm not the sharpest fork in the drawer, but after this odd business with the sword, I'm starting to think that maybe I need to change that. Our job's more'n just scrapping with thieves─sometimes we need to use our heads.
I've been spending my spare time learning how to tinker with this and that over at the manufactory. Should come in handy seeing how we handle firearms in the Hounds.
For years we've been spittin' curses at the blue bloods from the shadows of the Brume, but at long last we've found ourselves a place in the sun. I'm glad I chose to throw my lot in with the Mongrel.
Bah, I can't believe we let that bastard get away. Feels like the mission ain't truly over till we catch him, but maybe that's just me.
If Rostnsthal hadn't pointed it out, I never even would've guessed there was someone else pullin' the strings. I s'pose we're still new to this investigatin' business, eh?
Hilda says the Hounds'll be doin' some trainin' alongside the Temple Knights. Probably best that we know how the other does things so's we don't end up steppin' on each other's toes.
The watch has its detractors, but it has its supporters as well. House Dzemael has become one of our staunchest allies, and Lord Tedalgrinche himself has been championing our cause.
Ishgard is changing for the better, my friend, and Hilda rides the crest of that wave. I pray you see to it that she and her colleagues are not pulled under or swept away.

I remember well the day I met young Hilda. I shan't dwell on the details, but the first words she had for me were...bracing, to say the least. And yet, my prospectometer chirped in her presence, even as it did in yours.
'Tis with a deep well of emotion that I see her now at the forefront of Ishgard's social revolution. Glad I am that my gift to her put a sliver of doubt into her previously unshakable prejudices.
Ah, MistressMaster  . You honor us with your presence. Are you enjoying the sights in Kugane?
I have been giving considerable thought as to how best go about introducing Eorzean fashion to my homeland. I expect to be enlisting your services sooner rather than later.
MistressMaster  . Ever since Kotocho took the stage wearing your marvelous creation, orders for Eorzean fashions have been trickling in slowly but surely.
Needless to say, it will take time until Western aesthetics find wide acceptance, but in the meantime, it is heartening to know our efforts have not gone for naught.
MistressMaster  , thank you for coming. Both Kotocho and I truly appreciate your concern.
It is a hard time for her, but do not worry. She is a strong girl, and she will emerge from this hardship all the stronger─I am sure of it.

MistressMaster  ! I am pleased to say that after Kotocho and Kototsuru's legendary performance, orders have been pouring in night and day! It is all Yagiri and I can do to keep up─not that I am complaining, of course.
Meanwhile, Kotocho has firmly staked her claim as Kototsuru's successor atop the Hanamachi. Everyone who is anyone in Kugane names her their favorite.
And yet, whenever I go to meet her, she is still the same, sweet, humble girl I have ever known her to be. I do not deserve one as beautiful as her in my life, yet I cherish her all the same.

Welcome to Daitenya, purveyor of the finest silks and garments in Kugane. Our name is taken from Daitenzan, the mightiest peak in Hingashi, and symbolizes our unwavering resolve to achieve the absolute height of elegance and fashion.

Master Keimei recently took over the business from his dear father, and has made it his personal mission to uphold the proud tradition of the Daitenya name, while also introducing worldly fashions befitting our modern age.
MistressMaster  . I am pleased to report that Eorzean fashions are beginning to find a receptive audience among the Kugane elite.
At first, I too was skeptical, but there is something about your work─a universal quality that touches one's very soul. I cannot thank you enough for all you have done on our behalf.
Welcome back to Daitenya, MistressMaster  ! Thanks to you, business is better than ever. These days, Daitenya rises high above all our competitors─just as the great peak from which we take our name.
Speaking personally, I have been pleased to observe that it is not merely the wealthy, but the commonfolk as well have turned an eye to Eorzean fashions.
Still, it would seem the young master has bigger dreams still. I suspect he will be calling on your services again soon.
MistressMaster  ! I cannot thank you enough for all you have done. Thanks to you, my career as a geiko has been a success beyond my wildest dreams!
Just between the two of us, there are times when I wonder if I truly deserve this success, and I lose heart.
But when I do, I look at this dress. I think of all the sacrifices that you and Master Keimei made for me─and I vow to myself that I will make you proud.
Live, love, and craft to fulfill the needs of others─that is the way of the carpenter. From this day forward, that is exactly what I shall be doing!
, you and Timbermaster Beatin have helped me come to an important understanding of what it means to be a carpenter.
I shall continue to practice, practice, and practice some more that I might one day become as good as the two of you!
Hey,  . Have you seen our mount? Hearer Marmaduke said we can keep it here for everyone to see. A shame Miss Atelloune isn't here to speak with all the people who stop by.

I'll have so much to tell her when she gets back, and show her as well. Thanks to all of Guildmaster Geva's teachings, I bet I'll even be able to make an animal mount all by myself by the time she returns.

Between you and me... I've never been that skilled at astrology. Two winters here and I still haven't opened a single heaven. I can't even spell half of the ridiculous terms we're supposed to memorize!
But since the arrival of that mysterious Easterner, I seem to have found a renewed interest in his body─I mean, my studies!
Now that Kyokuho is gone, it is back to assisting the Lady Leveva with her preparations for the symposium. At least the work keeps my mind off his arse─I mean, my mind on the stars!

The symposium was a success, and now there is news that Kyokuho may soon return to the Athenaeum to resume his studies! Perhaps Lady Leveva will put us in the same kisses─I mean, classes! In the same classes.
While I am happy for Lady Leveva, the Vault's newfound interest in Sharlayan astrology has increased our workload here tenfold.
Alright, that may be an exaggeration. Sevenfold, then! And not a fold less!
When Chief Astrologian Forlemort assigned me here for “further training” I knew my accidental killing of his cat in that experiment with the Earthly Star was not to be forgiven.

But now that Lady Leveva's teachings have garnered the attention of the Vault, it appears our stars have finally risen. The arrival of the brilliant and talented and handsome and talented Kyokuho is just further proof of this!
He's gone...and he didn't even say good-bye.
Now, I look up into the heavens and all I see is the black of the void. Even the stars refuse to smile anymore...
Have you heard the news? Of course you have! But I'll tell you anyway!

They have made me an assistant professor at the Scholasticate! I will be teaching Lady Leveva's courses to all the young, handsome students... Oh, and the old, ugly ones as well. Of course. Why wouldn't I?

Why hello,  ! If you haven't noticed, the Athenaeum is practically abuzz with talk of wind, water, and the optimal position of your bed pillows if you wish to avoid ill fortune in commerce. In other words, it hasn't changed since Kyokuho arrived...

To keep her mind off Kyokuho's sudden return to his homeland, Lady Leveva has buried herself in the preparations for her symposium, locking herself in her alcove for days on end. Free from her usual nagging, I've found myself with a considerable amount of time on my hands...and decided to take up fortune-telling! Allow me to read your future.
Ahem... The Bole...then the Spire...then over here goes the inverted Arrow...then down here another Arrow... Wait! Another Arrow? Who put two arrows in my deck!? If I find out who did this─!
We have seen quite a change in Lady Leveva since her little sojourn in the Far East.

Where once one could rarely find her in her study for the wanderlust which kept her ever abroad, she now has taken to remaining within the city's walls, content on guiding budding young minds to bloom.
Ahhh, Shirogane... One day─one day I'll wake up to your pristine white sands...
We won,  . We...we won...
I gave you leave to come and go as you like. So go.
You are returned. For what purpose? To wait until the Naadam as part of a stratagem? Hah! Do as you will...but know I will come for you first.
Best of luck to you in all your revolutionary endeavors. After all, the Empire takes a dim view of free trade, whereas the company is of, how shall I put this...rather the opposite opinion.
You needn't worry about the other units. I am well aware of their disposition and will see that each receives the necessary support.
'Twas heartbreaking to watch the keep collapse...but I know it had to be done. We can and will rebuild, for we are free, my friend. We are free!
Today is the day for which we have trained body and mind with passion and vigor! We will not fail─Doma will be free!
They will use everything at their disposal to defend against our assault. All their men and all their magitek...and mayhap the twisted hybrids spoken of only in hushed whispers...
We have begun studying the magitek used in the defense of Doma Castle. There may be a way to repurpose it for the reconstruction efforts...
The memory of our defeat a year ago still burns within me. Yotsuyu and her imperial dogs will pay for their crimes!
Doma belongs to her people once more! We could not have achieved this great victory without the help of so many. You and yours will not be forgotten!
As I am not skilled enough to stand on the front lines with the others, I will remain here in reserve. But have no doubt that I can and will fight...
I need an adventurer with crafting experience. If you've a steady hand and a keen eye, I might have some work for you.
How am I supposed to concentrate on my duties with the sea taunting me like this? My hand itches for a fishing rod, it does...
Ah,  ! Work on the Gobroller is proceeding as planned for the moment. I shall be in touch again when we need you to mine something for us.
It is time for one last push! There may have been a few problems along the way, but now everything is in place for us to succeed.
, how nice of you to stop by! We are still in the midst of testing the Gobroller prototype.

The more tests we run, the more issues we find. At times it all feels a bit overwhelming, but I know we can overcome whatever issues the project throws our way. The previous performance test is proof of that!
Pshhh... Shkohhh... Splendid to have a miner of your caliber on board! I can fully concentrate on my own work knowing that we shall not want for the minerals we require.
Pshhh... Shkohhh... Founding this manufactory was far from easy. Working with Rowena in particular was a challenge the likes of which I had never encountered before.
However, seeing how far the team has come makes me certain that my struggles were all worthwhile.
It's hotter than Ifrit's arse after a peck of dragon peppers.

Now that I think of it, I'm certain I've heard your name somewhere before. Yes, a legendary miner that just so happens to be an equally legendary adventurer. If you're even half as good as the stories, I'm sure we'll have no cause to regret hiring you.

Fohcwyda has quite the mind! She thought to carve glyphs into each type of sheet metal to help with combining them. Such an idea would never have come to me; her help is going to make all the difference!

I was not aware of it until now, but I had never stopped to truly consider what it meant to work at the Bangpots. I must thank you and Nonowato for opening my eyes. I am ready to see this project through to the end.
! Word of your recent adventures has reached us even here in Idyllshire. You may no longer be mining for us, but you continue to be a great source of inspiration.
I cannot see worth a damn in this wretched thing!

Thrilled to pieces to have you here, friend! You may find us to be a somewhat eccentric bunch, but I am sure you will come to enjoy our company in due course. My advice: enjoy the journey─we are on the verge of greatness!

I have been researching the anatomy of other races and it has proved to be quite an enlightening experience. Did you know an average Roegadyn female's foot is approximately three times as long as a Lalafell's knee is wide?

Sorry for how long it has taken to sort ourselves out,  . But do not worry, it will all have been worth it when you are able to feast your eyes on our glorious Gobroller! Please continue to lend us your pickaxe until that time comes.

When I was working on the Gobroller's controls with Stackblox, I developed quite an interest in the anatomy of various races. I have challenged myself to create a single set of controls that is equally convenient for the biggest of Roegadyn and the tiniest of Lalafells.
It might help if I had some ink to go with this quill.
It is truly quite amusing. Just as I had been wishing we had someone else to help realize our vision, you appeared! Just to check, you are positive you cannot read minds, yes?
Krystrymm is considering boosting the armor's defenses by inserting elementally charged jewels directly into the sheet metal. Who knew he had such a magnificent brain beneath that thick skull?

It is all well and good just throwing yourself head first into your work, but we really could have done with being a bit more flexible. I should have listened to my own words when I complained about Krystrymm refusing to adapt to a different way of thinking. My apologies for involving you,  .
Hello again,  ! We have heard much of your latest adventures─it sounds like you are having quite the journey. Do not hesitate to ask for our succor should you require it.
Pshhh... Shkohhh... Gobbies and uplanders sweatworking together to make new technology!
Pshhh... Shkohhh... Plenty of rocks in Stickqix's Bangpots, but Stackblox needs uplander to mine more!
Pshhh... Shkohhh... Uplanders and gobbies are not so different. Stackblox and Zansei will fancycraft whirlycog insides that suit all races!
Pshhh... Shkohhh... Stackblox should have done more hand-lending for the others. Stackblox won't make the same mistake twice!
Pshhh... Shkohhh... There is nothing uplanders and gobbies can't achieve together. The future is bright!
May the gods spare me further bloodshed and let me live out my days in peace, as a humble trader. I have no talent for war...
From traveler to warrior, and now to khagan. What will you become next, I wonder?
Khagan, know you will always be of the Mol, wheresoever you go. Ours is the soil.
So it is true... A falling star bears down upon us from the heavens.
As always, I stand with you. If there is aught Kazagg Chah can do to aid, you need but say the word.
My friend. In all my years, I have seen no mage attain the heights of power you now possess. I stand in awe and amazement.
But pray forgive me my empty words. After all, your mastery of our art has been recognized by none other than Lady Shatotto herself.
I will say only this─I am honored to know you and call you friend.
All heals with time, and I am no exception. If I am needed for the next Naadam, I will be ready.

The other day, I stumbled into a body between here and the Sepulchre. Done in by the Corpses, most like. Don't know who the poor sod was, but he was Ala Mhigan, far as I could tell. Couldn't well just leave him there, so I took the liberty of burying him.
Father has dreamed of this day for nearly half his life. Just one more step.
I've trained with countless weapons, but none compare to Tizona. That Father saw fit to honor me in this way still fills my heart with pride...
You are a wise womanman, Commander. The duty of the strong is, and always will be, to protect the weak.
I cannot believe I will have the chance to work with Fufucha and you,  ! I will do my best not to disappoint, although I can't promise anything...
I promise I will prove myself worthy of the title of first botanist of Idyllshire. It's the least I can do to repay Fufucha's faith.
I've thought about the path, and whether I want to walk it myself someday. But after everything that happened with Myste, I think I might want to pursue conjury instead.
Sometimes we have to do bad things for good reasons. I know that, I do...but I'd still rather try to avoid it if I can. If I was a better healer, then maybe I'd have more options...or something.
That Padjal, ESumiYan. I could write him a letter...
Is it true that you have come from the far side of the world solely to aid us in our fight? If so, then you have my utmost gratitude.
How bold of you and Lady Yugiri to face Zenos by yourselves! But reckless too, I must say. Had either of you perished in the attempt, it would have been a terrible blow to our cause.
Eleven...<huff>...twelve... <puff> If I am to help free Doma from the yoke of imperial oppression, I must train my body to its physical peak! A daily regimen of vigorous exercise is essential!
One hundred and eleven...<huff>...one hundred and twelve... <puff> Pain is but weakness leaving the body! Pain is but weakness leaving the body!
More allies to aid the Doman Liberation Front? We should be glad to receive you!
That you and Lady Yugiri and all of the villagers returned alive is nothing short of a miracle...
If the tales are to be believed, you are a warrior of peerless skill. I pray they are no exaggeration.
Failure or not, that you held your own against Zenos in a duel for even a moment is a testament to your strength!
As you have seen, we are few in number and our resources are limited. Our every action must be planned with care, for we can ill afford to suffer losses.
...Any mission from which one returns alive is, in my opinion, not a failure.
Ah,  , welcome back. You are looking well. Tell me, how is that lecherous forgemaster of yours doing?
To scour the sweeping seas for a single species of fish, root out the reason for its rapid disappearance, and save it from certain extinction...
A tall task, this is true, but one worthy of Wawalago and his wealth of wits and wisdom!
Sisipu's still steaming about my surreptitious little sojourn in Isari. Why can't the girl just forgive and forget, I say?
She's watching me with as wary an eye as ever. Hah, but worry not─that hasn't stopped me from sneaking out to my favorite fishing holes!

I have heard all about your most recent adventures from Reyna and Master Wawalago. Oh, if only I could join you on your search for these shooting stars─what I would not give to see them with my own two eyes!
I daresay that taking part in the Wadatsumi festival was the most fun I've had as a fisherman in─well, as long as I can remember. You have my gratitude for letting me join you.
The rebuilding of our homeland will be no less demanding than our efforts to reclaim it. We will need to train our bodies to their physical peaks! Daily and no less rigorously than before!
To my relief, there was no need for me to take the field. Now I am free to lay down my blade and devote my energies to the rebuilding of our nation!

For an age, I felt as if time had stopped for me. But now, for the first time since Nielle passed, I feel as though I can move forward. And so I will, but ever will I carry with me the memory of him and our time together.
When I first knew I'd lost my memories, I was confused. Frightened, even.
But ever since I started training as a red mage, it's as if none of that matters anymore. Thanks to you and X'rhun, I have so much to look forward to! My life is my own.
How Revenant's Toll has changed since last I was here! Naught makes a man feel his age as much as knowing how things were and seeing how things are!
One never knows when they might be attacked on the Steppe. Doubly true now that we have won the Tsagaan Sar.
Now the Tsagaan Sar has come to a close there will doubtless be plenty of merchants keen to resume trading. I will need to make sure I have an ample supply of wares to sell.
I wonder whose spirit will find its way into my child's body. I eagerly await the day when the khatun is at last able to gaze into my baby's eyes.
Do not disturb me. I must be ever vigilant. This does not change now that Tsagaan Sar is over.
"SheHe who fights with strength of stone unyielding, breathes deep of boundless sky and embraces serenity of rolling sea, against herhim none can stand.“
...I haven't the foggiest what in the hells it means, but you've got to admit that it sounds like something a clever man would say.
Hello there,  ! I trust things are well with you. They couldn't be better with me and my little kitty. He is just the sweetest thing!
...Hm? H'mhasi who? I'm sure I've no idea who that worthless piece o' turd is.
, allow me to thank you again. I've always looked up to you, and it's nothing short of a dream come true to have your help.
Don't worry,  . No matter what, I've no intention of giving up. I've learned that much from you.
, great to see you. The café is doing well, I'm happy to say. Folk are coming from far and wide just for our Far Eastern dishes.
Things are positively rosy with Anzu and her father, too. Life's good, all in all, and I've nothing to complain about.

...Well, to be completely honest, my fire for adventure has flared up again, and in my spare time I've been off collecting tomestones with the old crowd. Needless to say, not a word of this to anyone!
Delta IV eliminated. No more Deltascape subjects remain. Initiating world shutdown.
We await good tidings from the Far East, my friend. In the meantime, the Alliance will continue to aid the Resistance and help it to rebuild.
Glad to have you with us again. Hmm...you seem stronger than I remember─hard though I find that to believe. One would almost think you'd spent the whole time fighting. Well done, by the way.
We bought this freedom with blood. That of our friends and our enemies. I'll be damned if we're going to give it up again.
...Be honest: is it unbecoming? I am told there are those whose heads are suited to the style, but never did I consider mine to be one.

Apropos of nothing, allow me to thank you for your deeds in service to the Holy See of Ishgard. I understand you were instrumental in bringing an end to the Dragonsong War, thereby saving countless lives from a fiery doom.
I say this, of course, only as a man concerned for the welfare of his fellow man, as I have no vested interest in the affairs of the cold and dreary North.

I daresay our voyage to the Far East was one of my most profitable yet. We had the good fortune to meet with many vessels on the way back, all of which were eager to trade─and with such generous terms, I might add.
The days ahead are dark indeed, and so we will aid you to the best of our ability. May you walk with the Warden ever at your side.
All is well, all is well. My daughter lives, and our homeland is free. Blessed are we to have come through the fires so unscathed...
Keep an eye on my daughter, would you? And yourself while you're at it.
I am glad to see the imperials driven from our lands, but more than that I am relieved that my daughter survived the campaign. Doubtless I have you to thank for that...
Now comes our part to think on the future. For the Ala Mhigan refugees in Ul'dah to decide whether or not they want to return and help rebuild...
Our bloody campaign is ended, and we may begin to return home. That said, our work is far from finished. We've yet countless wounded to tend to, not to mention prisoners of war...

Seven hells, is it true? Did you really best Zenos and that bastard primal─just you and seven stalwart adventurers whom you had the wisdom and foresight to recruit? No wonder they call you a bleedin' hero!
What can you do at a time like this other than curse the gods and your own powerlessness...
I should have been there with you to the end. If only I hadn't been so reckless...
I swear to the Twelve and all the kami in creation, if he says another word about politics and organizations, I'm going to scream.
Master Kemp seems quite shaken...
We'll find Krile and bring her home. After all, I need her to tell you to stay in bed.

What sort of nation is Ala Mhigo to become? That is the question on the lips of every man, woman, and child in Gyr Abania. Establishing an interim government after a twenty-year occupation is a massive undertaking, never mind running it.
In these crucial first days the Scions must offer our full support, or else everything we fought to achieve could be lost.
I should've died a thousand times over, but I'm still here, and I owe it all to the friends─nay, the family who fought by my side. I owe them everything.
I'll continue to serve as a proud member of the Resistance! Though, now that I say it...if there's nothing left to resist, does it make any sense to go on calling ourselves the Resistance?
Even assuming that the people of Gyr Abania need not fear imperials or primals or other threats, there are yet other places fraught with peril, where innocents cry out for heroes. We could be them.
I set out on this journey with a single goal, and it has been achieved. Once more do I put up my spear, this time for good, I think. Arenvald and the other young ones can carry on in my stead.

Though I was born in Ul'dah, my mother's actually from Ala Mhigo, so you could say this is my half-homeland, which makes this my half-homecoming, but I find myself wholly touched to be in this awe-inspiring place!
Orders have been flooding in from Ul'dah and it's all we can do to keep pace, but thanks to the fine spectacles you crafted for me, I can tackle all that work with clarity and confidence!
Things are chaotic here as always, but it's nice to have some old faces nearby.

Carryin' the Gemworks name, I feel pride an' pressure at the same time. Mostly pressure, to be honest. But then I think back to your masterpieces, an' it reminds me that the most important thing is betterin' myself.
I had no idea you fight for the Resistance as well! It's like you're good at everything!

Er, Schoolmaster? Is it true the Syndicate picked you for this job? ...No? But Wido said─
...Godsdammit, not again! How do I keep on falling for his hogwash!?
While they are still green in many ways, our apprentices are undeniably gifted. Best not to tell them that, though, lest it make them complacent.
Ah, Schoolmaster, what a pleasant surprise. Lest you wonder, all is very well here. In spite of our youth, the Gemworks is already a respected name, and it's in no small part due to your leadership.
I am given to underssstand that, when three children of man of mixed gender gather, there is guaranteed to be ssstrife. I am curiousss to see what happens between our apprenticesss.
Our apprenticesss seem to get along very well. Not a hint of the ssstrife I was told to expect when three young ones of mixed gender are gathered. I must confesss to being a little disappointed.
, pray accept mine apologies and gratitude both for agreeing to the request in spite of its abruptness.
Her Grace has every faith in you, as do I, and I wish you every success in the initiative─not only as one who is involved, but as a humble citizen of the realm as well.
I am truly heartened to see the Crown Gemworks achieve so much in the short time it has been in operation.
All of this was made possible thanks to your tireless efforts and, of course, Her Grace's astute choice of schoolmaster.
If truth be told, I was aware of your observing Lady Lilira from the shadows in the markets. Knowing you, though, I believed that you had good reason, and so pretended not to notice.
Suffice it to say I was beyond delighted to see the lovely orchestrion you and yours had crafted for my lady. You truly made her day, and in so doing made this old man's as well!

It feels like only yesterday that you walked up to this counter, fresh-faced and eager to learn goldsmithing. But here you are now, among the lauded ranks of those who not only practice, but teach our craft. Seeing you come so far, I cannot help but feel a sense of pride.

Yet, by the same token, I cannot help but feel a little worried too. As I am sure you will appreciate, goldsmiths have a high profile in our city, and you are liable to attract more attention, for better or worse, like the guildmaster does. Do take care, now.
, my honored friend! What a pleasure to see you here in the enclave!

At the risk of repeating myself, Doma owes you and yours a debt that can never be repaid. And before you think to say it, our part in the siege of Ala Mhigo does not even begin to redress the balance.
Perchance you wonder how we fare? As you can see, our work is far from finished, but have no doubt we are wholly committed to the task. One day you will look on this place in wonder!
Oh,  ! That you are here can only mean that all is well in Ala Mhigo? That is good to hear...

For our part, Yanxia continues to enjoy a measure of peace. Our efforts to spread word of the rebellion in other provinces were successful in spreading unrest, and so it would seem we have successfully forestalled any reprisals by the imperials.

Doubtless events in Ala Mhigo have only served to strengthen the narrative of an Empire weak and in disarray. It will only last for a time, of course, and so we must never take our eyes from the enemy...but for now, we are free to rebuild. To begin anew.
Both my house and the smithy next door were reduced to rubble. Bah! Just give me a roof to put over my tools...
The Empire's forces are no more to be seen, but our people yet suffer in the aftermath. It is in times like this that pleasant distractions are the most welcome...

The people of Namai have been most generous with their rice. Before we were at the mercy of the imperials and their restrictions, but now we have food enough to feed our people, that they may have the strength to rebuild!
I mislike the sight of that imperial tower on the docks. Mayhap we can use it for our own ends, but I would much rather see the wretched thing razed to the ground.
Let me know what needs doing, and I'll see it done.
We must rebuild the enclave if we are to restore our nation to its former glory. People from all across Yanxia are coming here to join in the work. My family, too, will join me soon.
Enthusiasm is all well and good, but we cannot permit people to build whatever wherever they please! I am drafting a comprehensive reconstruction plan to present to Lord Hien for his approval.

Do not misunderstand. I am searching the rubble for valuables not for personal profit, but to further the reconstruction efforts. Their former owners should be glad to see them repurposed for this great endeavor!
Curious about my armor, are you? You are not the first. Upon beholding it, many have said they were taken by a strange sense of nostalgia. If you like, I would be happy to trade it with you.
Zenos took many of my brothers to the West as slaves to fight in his army. When they return, as I know they will, we shall welcome them home to a Doma reborn!
These caves make for a natural hideaway, and could be easily defended in the event of an attack. That said, the entrance is not the most convenient...
Oh,  ! What happened to the villagers? Are they all right? Do you need my help?
Yotsuyu was once a spy for the Liberation Front. She used her talents to beguile imperial officers and learn secrets which she shared with us...
Little did we know it was all in service to a larger plan: to ingratiate herself with us, that she might betray us to Zenos when he marched on Doma. And it worked.
This may be our final chance to win Doma her freedom. We dare not take any chances, for if we fail...
Much has changed in my absence. The state of the enclave, in particular, concerns me...
But it would seem Alphinaud understands the importance of ensuring their safety. You Scions are no ordinary mercenaries, that much is plain.
...I have seen you in my dreams, traveler.
You have been entrusted with a great task. Do not underestimate the Dotharl. Especially the mad woman who leads them.
Ho, the khagan comes! I must confess, when I spoke with you and the Doman, I thought you no more than common warriors. Skilled, yes, but capable of such feats? Nay...
We will be watching you and yours during the Naadam. If your men impress, we will make them ours.
The gods saw fit to return you to us. But what of your comrades? Where are they?
May you treasure the morin khuur for years and years to come.
You wish to reaffirm our commitment to your cause? Be at ease, my friend. The Mol will answer Doma's call.
A new day dawns, and with it new challenges...
You have passed through your trials here unscathed, it is true. But every star must follow its own course. Be ready.
Though all Xaela know well the violence of war, the battle for Hien's castle was unlike anything I had ever seen. Such chaos and destruction...and death...
Only men may be of the Buduga. Such is the gods' will. And so we take from others fresh blood to sustain our tribe.
Alas, as our strength wanes, so too does our ability to sustain ourselves. Alliances become necessary, such as ours with the Oronir...
We too are “allies” now, I suppose. But who can say what the morrow will bring?
I hope he's not doing something foolish...
Everything well with the investigation? I sent a man to keep watch by the Yawn, by the way. You need to head back down, just let the fellow know.
Omega will stop at nothing─not even massacre─to find a stronger foe... Whose damfool idea was it to program a thing like that?
When they thought to make a self-evolving weapon, didn't it occur to them that things might get out of hand? Hmph! If I ever meet the creators, I'd give 'em some choice words!
Kweh?
That went better than expected! But let's not get ahead of ourselves here!
Call it a showmaster's instincts, but from the moment I met Musosai, I knew he was no ordinary old man. I knew he was going to bring in money, and lots of it!
It hasn't sunk in that Musosai is gone... I'm going to put my traveling on hold and remain in Ul'dah for a while.
Ah,  , always good to see you. So, did you decide to lend Makoto and her crew a hand after all? Seemed they could really use the help, and it'd be an opportunity to give the old man peace.
, a personal thanks from me for taking care of business in Hingashi. I've no doubt that Musosai sleeps more soundly now.

As for me, I've a mind to linger a while and scout out new talent to showcase.
...You wouldn't be interested, would you? People would pay good coin to see the sublime skills of an Eorzean samurai, returned from honing herhis art in the exotic Far East!
Samurai or no, I cannot believe that Makoto would see fit to take an ijin into our confidence. I shall speak plain: I do not approve of your presence here.
You may have dealt with the traitor Shiden, but it will take more than that ere I consider you a comrade.
But of course you had a secret to hide. I know not what is worse─that you were pupil to the craven Musosai, or that the captain is sister to the insurgent Ugetsu.
I am ashamed for having doubted you. I admired Kogarashi in my childhood, and I believe I speak for all here when I say that I am both honored and grateful for your aid.
If we are to defeat the forces of Ugetsu, we must be relentless in our training!
To think that our own would be seduced over to Ugetsu's side... It must be for want of training!
If even Captain Kongo could not defeat Ugetsu, no amount of training will avail us...
If we are to approach the mastery of Master Musosai and your good self, we must be relentless in our training!
You must be the foreign samurai whom Makoto called upon. I bid you welcome. Makoto trusts you, and so shall I.
So Lieutenant Shiden was a traitor... A sad turn of events. Close as they were, it must be especially hard for Makoto.
It has to be a lie... Makoto couldn't possibly be Ugetsu's sister...could she?
By defeating her brother, Makoto has severed all ties with her past. If there had been any who doubted her fitness as captain, there are certainly none now.
This is the Sekiseigumi─ Ah, 'tis you, my friend. Pray come in and take your ease.
Ye've the makings of a fine warrior. But don't you go forgettin' what ye learned here at the guild. All them fancy new techniques mean nothin' without good basics an' fundamentals.
Would that I had good news to report, but I fear that Karasu has proven as elusive as ever.

While I continue my search, I have asked Tsubame to tell the elders that I am pursuing, ah, a mysterious renegade ninja who stole the scroll from Lord Hanzo and fled to Eorzea. Thankfully, they have not yet questioned my telling of events.
Excuse me, but could I have a moment of your time?
Seems to me there's less food to go around than the last time I was here...
Eh? What's this about?
The captain's word is final. Can't say I didn't warn you.

All ties that bind a man must be renounced, without exception, if he is to find a place here. Former lovers and bitter enemies alike must learn to bury their past and work side by side, or else be cast out.
...No matter how deep a man's hatreds may run, he cannot let them dictate his actions. The good of the Confederacy takes precedence over all.
Beneath the waters to the west of SuinoSato lies a cave that will lead you to the Isle of Zekki. May the kami watch over and keep you.
