The fog of Yanxia has been likened to a shroud of silence. A gift of the kami, some say, that the people of these lands may enjoy quiet, peaceful lives...
Brother's still too shy to speak to Lady Yugiri, by the way. He can't even say thank you!
It is...comforting to see you hale and healthy. We heard tell that the great kami Susano revealed himself to you in the treasure vault...
'Twas not our intention to spur his intercession. At the very least, I pray it was not a wholly objectionable experience. Capricious he may be, but...boring he is not, no?

We are glad to have been of assistance to you and yours in the siege of Doma Castle. Now that peace reigns, it is our hope that we can build a lasting and...profitable relationship between us and the people of Doma.
Hmm... You seem more...refreshed and relaxed than before, as if a great weight has been lifted from your shoulders. As if you walk with the divine. That is well...
If ever you come across treasures precious and sacred, I pray you consider bringing them to us.
I know how much you cared for the samurai, and so I searched the waters once more ere I returned. Alas, like before, I found naught...
But take heart, my friend, for that may mean that he lives! The current is most swift, and it could well have carried him out to sea, to any number of islands...
Hancock tells me that you fought in a great battle in the West, and that you won. Is it true?
How wonderful! Kami are drawn to the victorious, and with them come great fortune. Mayhap even great treasure?
What the─ We heard you and the others left for Kugane! We wanted to thank you, of course, but we never had the chance...
I, uh, I suppose I could... Ahem. Thank you. For everything, that is... Anyway! I won't keep you. I know you have another war to fight.
Of all the people! I knew Lord Hien and the others went west to join in your fight, but I didn't think you would be coming back with him!
Still, it's a relief to see you alive and well. If you've got time, you should stay a while. I'm sure the others would be glad to see you.
So I hear the little miss has a twin brother, who by all accounts is quite the strategist. I pray he is indeed every bit her equal.
I am told you have been busy. As have we, lest you wonder. None here shall perish for want of proper treatment.
Been to the Peaks and back, have you? Glad to see you're in good health.
More men means we need more arms and armor, but we'll find a way. We've come this far, haven't we?
Oh, where to begin? Thank you, perhaps. Your companions are still in the West, then? A pity. I truly did enjoy their company. Swagger and all.

Now that our many battles are ended, we can return to our old way of life. Alas, this means that you will be expected to pay the Ruby Tithe on subsequent visits.
...Oh, do not scoff. It is merely a Hingan jest!
Well, well, well! What a pleasant surprise this is!
We shall observe the Red for a time. If they withdraw from Isari, I shall consider this proof of your deeds, and we will strike.
Doma yet languishes in peril, but I trust that is in spite of your efforts. The Empire's eyes remain firmly fixed upon us, but we will endure for as long as we are able. We believe in you, my friend.
I am familiar with the plan, and I support it wholeheartedly. At the appointed hour, we will strike at the heart of Doma with all our might. Together we will triumph, or together we will fall.
...I distinctly recall taking you to Kugane that you might return to the West with all haste. But I suppose there is an ebb and flow to war, and a reason you can afford to be here for a time.
...Twenty-five years ago, when Doma first fell to the Empire, my family was murdered by imperial soldiers.
For a long, long time I believed that no one had the strength to stand against them. But I never forgot that scared little boy, and I never stopped hoping I was wrong. And I was.
I thought her possessed of greater sense than this. Why is she so eager to risk everything with this mad plan?
It might be stupid and reckless, but if she's going to do it anyway, then maybe...

Everything in Yanxia proceeding according to keikaku? Very good. I must confess that I was most saddened to see Master Alphinaud go, but duty calls and so forth. Rest assured that Tataru and I will keep you abreast of all developments we deem worthy of your attention.

I can see it now. Confederate ships sailing up the One River, equipped with the finest Lominsan-made cannons, provided by the East Aldenard Trading Company. The world is not as big as it once was, my friend.
I say, I consider myself to be a man of impeccable timing, attuned to the rhythms of the cosmos...and I have a sinking suspicion you shouldn't be here. Not yet, that is.
Setting your sights on Ala Mhigo next, I presume? Excellent. The chairman is most interested in seeing how that whole affair plays out.
Hm? Is the company willing to openly aid the Gyr Abanian campaign? Oh, heavens no. Far too close to home. 'Twould be an unconscionable risk.
First Doma, then Ala Mhigo. Well done you. I doubt not even the chairman expected you to be so damn good at warmaking!
Owing to your efforts, the company is now free to expand into several emerging markets. At the risk of waxing poetic, I think this may be the beginning of a beautiful friendship.

Who knows─we may even come to call one another “aibou,” as the Hingans do. 'Tis a most deep and meaningful word, aibou─some translate it as “friend,” but I think it better not to even bother trying, so unique and quintessentially Hingan the concept is...
All's quiet at the Garlean embassy─so far as we can tell from the outside. Anyway, carry on with the Doman business! We have matters here well in hand. Trust me!
Oh,  ! You didn't come all this way just to see little ol' me, did you? Silly me, of course not! You want the latest news about the Garlean embassy, don't you?
We've observed visitors from Garlemald coming and going from the embassy day and night. I think it's fair to say that events in Doma have them very, very concerned.
Congratulations,  ! You all managed to beat the bad guys and win the war! Then everything is wrapped up in a neat little package!
I suppose it's a little more complicated where Lyse is concerned, but she's got to follow her heart, and I'd rather be happy for her. I hope you are too!
Ordinarily I teach but one student at a time, but it will be a refreshing challenge to instruct the two of you together. I look forward to the experience.
How fares your craft,  ? As a teacher, there is no greater joy than seeing a former apprentice excel in our chosen art.
Have you gained a feel for the Hingan style of armorsmithing? I am here should you have any questions for a senior apprentice!

When time permits, I have been learning the Eorzean style of armorsmithing from Blanstyr. Providing you with materials has given me some idea, but there are so many differences in method and technique!
I have given the Doman my word, and I will not break it. Call upon us when you are ready, and no sooner.
...And spare me the company of the udgan, if you would.
We have fought, and the Doman has reclaimed his homeland. May he and his people have joy of it.
I am told you were victorious in yet another war in the West. Hardly surprising. For you are the khagan...for now.
Seasons turn, and bodies mend. Even Brother Baatu, once bedridden, has regained his former strength.
How fortunate he was to be wed to a woman so skilled in the arts of healing. How...fortunate...indeed.
It warms my heart to see you again,  , and to have a chance to congratulate you on your great victory in the West!
As Bardam's deeds endured for generations, so too shall yours. In our songs, and in the songs of your people. So it is always with they who walk in crimson.
Cirina told me of the samurai's fate. You have my deepest condolences, child.

The design can be difficult to discern for those within it. So it was when Cirina brought Hien unto us, bleeding and broken. Yet from that tragedy he rose, strong and resolute, and reclaimed what was lost...
Well met, Ssscions. I am Vajra. She who shines bright and unbroken.
I ssstand ready. We leave upon your command.
What's that? You wonder if I am an Adarkim?
Hahaha! Y-You are quite a comedian. No, no, I am just a regular piggy. Even if I were an Adarkim─which I'm not─I wouldn't dream of trying to become the next khan.
Someone with such dreams would be putting their very life at risk! Adarkim males will do anything to become khan─or so I hear. Now be off with you! Here, have some buuz for the road.
Why, Father? Why?

My father, he...he didn't make it...
They killed him! Those thrice-damned imperials killed him!
I thought long and hard about walking away after what happened to my father. But the others, they convinced me it was better to stay the course. That's what my father would've wanted, after all...
Ala Mhigo is ours! Ala Mhigo is free! At long last, my father can rest in peace...
All of my wares have gone up in smoke. I almost wish the fire had taken me too. I've nothing left...
I suppose the wise course of action would be to pack up what little I've got left and leave...but I've never been all that clever. It may take an eternity to rebuild what I've lost, but I will.
Been a while since you came through, aye? As you may have noticed, things are looking up in the Reach!
With freedom comes prosperity, my friend! In time I'll build a fortune to rival any Ul'dahn merchant prince!
I'm pathetic. Everyone's off fighting for Ala Mhigo and I'm stuck here with my useless arm.
They say you helped liberate our home. Thank you. I wish I could've been out there fighting with you.
Everyone here has been on edge of late. No one's quite sure just what is going on in Gyr Abania.

I've decided not to make the move. It's been so long since we first arrived here it feels more like home than Ala Mhigo ever could. What's more, should Ala Mhigo want to trade more with Ul'dah, they'll need someone to act as an intermediary.
On my good days, I've been able to help out Alfan with his work. He's been making medicine to send to those putting their lives on the line for Ala Mhigo.
Me chest is burning...<wheeze>...with the fire that inspired my brethren to take back our home. Ugh, I feel like I'm dying, but I couldn't be happier.
Everyone's been so excitable of late. Keep wonderin' if there ain't somethin' I can do to help too.
Can you bleedin' believe it? They've only gone and freed Ala Mhigo. Can't remember a time I was last this happy.
I have been working together with Meffrid to see that all the refugees are given shelter and properly fed. It is no easy task, but it is our duty to protect these people.
I have heard about Meffrid... Slain by a fellow Ala Mhigan. I cannot believe it. I do not want to believe it.

For a while there I was overcome by anger and grief. The captain did not deserve such a cruel fate. However, I eventually realized that he would have been appalled to see me moping around in such a state. It is time I did my part so that I do not dishonor his memory.
Now that the fighting has finished, I would very much like to visit Rhalgr's Reach and pay my respects to the captain.
To think you would end up liberating my homeland. You have my sincerest thanks,  . Though words will never be enough to truly express my gratitude.
Now I simply need decide whether to stay here or move back to Ala Mhigo. I'm sure it's quite a bit nicer now those imperial whoresons have been driven out.
<cough> <wheeze> Well, I can hardly die now, can I? I've got to see Ala Mhigo once more with my own eyes.
No one is happier than me to see Ala Mhigo liberated, of that you can be certain.
However, it is too early to be patting ourselves on the back. The Empire still has plenty of troops in reserve, and we do not yet know if the Corpse Brigade will attempt to reclaim power.
Oh gods, don't tell me you came all the way back here just to look in on me? That's kind of you, but really, you should be with the others in the Lochs, finishing what we started. Go, go!
, you are returned!
! That you are here gives me cause to hope!

Our victory at Castellum Velodyna has earned us a strong foothold here in Gyr Abania. But the road before us is still quite long. We will need to be duly prepared before our plans can proceed further.
Now that Ala Mhigo has been freed from the imperials, trade with Gridania is likely to increase. It falls to us to ensure any trade lines established remain safe.
Aye, we've won, but our work is far from done. The people of Ala Mhigo are faced with the not-so-small task of rebuilding their lives, and it's our duty to help them.
Castellum Velodyna is ours! With this victory, we are one step closer to guaranteeing the freedom of Ala Mhigo and her people.

The greater part of our work here in Ala Mhigo is done, but it seems duty would bid me stay here a while longer. A small portion of our forces are still needed here, and I have been charged with overseeing the delivery of provisions from Ishgard.
At last, the fighting has stopped. It was all I could do to manage the constant shipments of provisions. Perhaps now I can make a proper record of our inventory.
Word has it you played a rather pivotal role in routing the Garleans. On behalf of the M tribe, you have our thanks. I pray those who fell in battle will at last find peace.
I'm glad to be rid of the Garleans, but it's no reason for us to let down our guard. There's still the threat of cloudkin to worry about.
Freedom, that virtue which Sri Lakshmi extols above all others, is ours once more. Yet there is no guarantee that it shall remain ssso. We must remain vigilant, now and ever after.

It ssseems the Garleans have finally fled. Though we mourn the losss of our sisters who fell in battle, we are also quite proud of their sacrifice, as we are of the great many others lost in the fighting.
Medicines, is it? Come on, come on, take what you need! I'm not about to be a stickler when there's lives to be saved!
Wish I could say it's gotten a lot better in your absence, but we still have trouble obtaining even the most basic supplies. Still, we make do with what we've got.
After what everyone's been through, I think I might rummage around and see if I can't find some spirits to pass around. If ever there were a time to bend the rules, this is it, aye?
Valiantly did we fight, but ultimately for naught...
Fassster! Fassster! Look them in their eyes and ssstrike them in their heartsss!
Fassster! Fassster! Wassste not these preciousss hours, but in quiet preparation make ssstrong the body and mind!
What's done is done. The dead are dead. All I can do is feed the living and pray it helps them to grow stronger.
For a while after the attack, folks ate their food in silence. Slowly but surely, though, things have gotten back to normal. They're starting to believe again...
A right and proper feast is long overdue, I say! We've got cause enough to celebrate, don't we?
Bastards paid no heed to whether or not the men they slaughtered were armed. Some of the sutlers... Damn it all!
The sutlers have pulled out all the stops and managed to secure us some new supplies. It may not be by much, but things are steadily improving.
I would have you remember that we owe a great deal to all the merchants that supplied us. Ala Mhigo could not have been freed without their help.
The imperials came from the Peaks. Somehow they knew about the tunnel...
Ala Mhigo may have been liberated, but the Empire is still out there. We must not let our guard down.
We came together as best we could, but in the end, there were just too many of them.
All of us are eager for a chance to strike back at the imperials. Our day is coming!
It's like the commander said: freedom for all, a home for us all. That's what we've won, and that's what we've got to defend from now on!
I don't know... If we'd noticed sooner we could've used the cannons, but by the time we did, it was too late...
They'll not surprise us again, oh no. We'll be ready next time─my cannons too!
I know you were busy dealing with Fordola and all those weapons in Castrum Abania, but if you'd been outside, you'd have seen my cannons sing!
There will be a reckoning. Mark my words...
Gyr Abania belongs to man and Ananta once more. Let us pray that it is always ssso.
No time to talk. I must prepare more medicines.
A healer's work is never ended. If anything, I'm busier than ever. But, for a mercy, I have medicines enough...
I know there were spare bandages here somewhere...
We still need all the bandages we can get. An awful lot of our men were wounded in the battle for Ala Mhigo...
Gah... In the heat of battle I barely felt the pain, but when the fighting died down, it was all I could do to stay standing...
The tide's turning, I can feel it! I've got to heal, got to get better...got to get back to the front with the others...
I recovered in time to join the siege...only to injure my shoulder again. But I was there! I stood shoulder to shoulder with my brothers and sang till my throat was hoarse!
Herbs for the poultices, herbs for the poultices...
All these new recruits and allies means that we'll need even more herbs! I've got to pick up the pace!

I know what you're thinking. “Hughoc, you don't need to keep gathering herbs for everyone. Can't somebody else do it?” And you're right, but the thing is...I like it! Damned if I know why, but I just can't stop!
I hope you like it hot, because the Moonfire Faire is here! This year the festivities are being held on the Isle of Endless Summer. Enjoy the heat while you can!
Not now. I'm busy. I've no time for idle chatter or more rumors. But gods, that last rumor... I can't get it out of my head.
You're doing the gods' work by helping with the Moonfire Faire. Nobody expected it to be such a success. We're all grateful for everything you adventurers have done.
As of now, no trouble has come of this treasure nonsense, and it looks as though the Bombards are staying away. There was a moment I thought this Moonfire Faire might go smoothly.
But that proved to be no more than a mummer's thought. The biggest problem is we don't have the staff to accommodate all these faire-goers. Please, friend, lend us a hand where you can.

The Moonfire Faire is being held here on the Isle of Endless Summer. And it is drawing more people than anyone thought possible. If you care to know more about the festivities, you need only speak to one of the faire chaperones.
! Allow me to thank you for your help with the faire. You know as well as any how shorthanded we always are. Feel free to lend a hand if you find the time.
Begging your pardon, but I am afraid I am extremely busy now. If you'd like to place an order, would you mind waiting a spell?
I've no idea what it is about the Moonfire Faire that makes everyone crazy for battered fish. Nobody gives it a second thought the rest of the year. What a strange thing, indeed.
The ingredients I prepared are nowhere near the amount we need for all these orders. The vegetables and seasonings I can acquire more of, but the fish... My gods, the fish!
Bugger me─we're still short on fish. Nobody could have possibly known we'd need this much.
Hello, and welcome to the Isle of Endless Summer. The isle is currently hosting the Moonfire Faire. I hope you find your stay a pleasant one.
I did what I could to promote the isle and draw as many visitors as possible to this year's faire. Based on what I've been hearing, it seems my labors have borne fruit.
I am grateful beyond words when I see everyone toiling to make the Moonfire Faire as great a success as possible. You adventurers are a gift from the gods, truly.
It is a relief to hear that the civilians in the Ala Mhigan Quarter are under our protection. However, there are still many others who are in danger...
I understand you rescued Krile, and that is well. But we have no time to pat ourselves on the back. Not while the battle for Ala Mhigo yet looms.
I heard you and yours caused quite a commotion in the quarter. A pity I was not there to enjoy it.
The scouts said the dragoon's armor was unmistakable. But surely he would not...

Even on the verge of this siege, Ser Aymeric will not forgo his tea. To see him drink it, so calm and composed, you would think him anywhere but a battlefield. You too are the picture of composure, though that is hardly surprising given your combat experience.
It's over, they say. As if all that blood'll wash away the years of pain...
In retrospect, I'm glad I chose to remain here. I cannot wait to welcome back all of my friends who left so long ago.
Knowing that I've paid my last tributum is a beautiful feeling. Maybe now I'll have enough money to enjoy myself once in a while.
I'm sorry, but I really must tend to these chocobos. Perhaps we can speak later.
If you need something it'll have to wait. I caught these two lackwits trying to shirk their duties, and they need a good dressing down.
Ala Ghiri used to be somethin' special. A place where folks from all over would gather an' do business. <sigh> I wonder how long till we get back to the way things were...
That crystal up there's a beauty, isn't it? You won't see one like it anywhere else.
Sorry, sweetling. I don't think you're quite ready for the games I like to play.
Sorry, lasslad. I'm in the middle o' business. You understand, right?
Gossip around town is that Ala Mhigo's been liberated from the Garleans? But that couldn't be true...could it?
Terribly sorry, but I have nothing an adventurer such as yourself could find useful. You might have better luck asking one of the other merchants here in town.
Whatever it is will have to wait. I need to take this gentleman's order.
You're looking parched, friend. How's about stopping by my tavern to put back a few?
So, the Empire has withdrawn...? I wonder if he knows...wherever he is now.
Change is always a time of opportunities. Now that Gyr Abania is free, there'll be a need for folk willing to start up a new trade.
Ah! Oh gods, I─ Well, I suppose the Empire's soldiers are long gone by now. I still don't care for being startled like that, though!
Ma said we could eat as soon as she finished. But that was a few bells ago...
If you're lookin' for a hot meal or a warm bed, you won't be findin' it here. To be honest, you won't be findin' much of anythin' here.
This is Isobe. A long time ago, I was returning from a business meeting with the Kojin in Tamamizu, when he appeared and followed me home. He has been with me ever since.
Isobe is an otter, and I cannot count the number of times I have told Her Highness as much. <sigh> She, however, continues to insist he is a wartfish...
Please,  . You have to find my brother. Heavens only know what trouble that lovesick fool has gotten himself into.
A group of the villagers have decided to join the fight to liberate Doma. I can only pray that they all come back safe and sound someday.
They did it! Doma is liberated at last!
All of my friends have returned! I did not think I would ever see the day.
It pains me more than I could ever express that I cannot fight alongside my fellow villagers. All I can do is pray for their success.
I never thought the day would come when our small village would be filled with war heroes. I am so proud of every single one of them.
Some of my friends returned just a short while ago. I have no idea if the Empire let them go, or if they escaped, but I am thrilled to see them safe regardless.
My friends say they are going to join the fight against the Empire and I have a mind to join them.
We did it! The Empire rules us no longer! Oh, I cannot wait to tell my daughter all about how we bested those imperial dogs.
The beauty of these flowers may be ethereal and fleeting, but that is precisely what makes them so precious.
Namai may be a sad village, but there is life left in it yet. Those willing to rebel against our imperial overlords prove that.

I do hope the village becomes a bit livelier now that we are free of the Empire. I still remember fondly how nice a place it was to live before the invasion. Hopefully I will live to see Namai's fortunes continue to improve in the near future.
The villagers! They have returned! They said something about being tricked by some woman. I am not sure exactly what they meant, but I am truly glad they are back where they belong.
All those capable of fighting have agreed to go rebel against the Empire. I would love nothing more than to join them, but I cannot even go to relieve myself without the aid of this cane.
I cannot believe it. We are finally free...
Now that the battle is ended, I suspect there will be a flood of Ala Mhigans seeking to return to their homeland. We must be prepared.
One does not neglect a patient once the wound has been stitched. No, I shall remain a while, and see that Gyr Abania is fully healed.

What a battle...
We paid for it in blood, but by Rhalgr, we won!
I wonder how many soldiers survived thanks to these brave birds! I think they deserve extra feed rations for a moon or two, don't you?
We've won for now, but the Empire won't relax its grip so easily. We need to keep our soldiers in fighting shape!
GCRankLimsaMaleTextGCRankGridaniaMaleTextGCRankUldahMaleText  ! Help yourself to a bowl of soup, if you'd like.
Seems we'll soon be turning our efforts to rebuilding. Our new orders should be coming in any day now!
Ala Mhigo will not soon forget your name,  . For my part, I'll be sure to teach it to my children's children!
Tales were told of your deeds in battle, GCRankLimsaMaleTextGCRankGridaniaMaleTextGCRankUldahMaleText  . Another chapter in the book of Eorzea's storied hero!
The battle is won, but our return to Limsa Lominsa will have to wait until we've sorted out the aftermath. Ah, if I could but step through a magical door into the Drowning Wench...
It was an honor to fight at the ssside of you and your allies.
Ah,  . We have seen a steady increase in people passing through here ever since the fighting ceased.
Damn it, Alisaie! This is serious! You need rest!
Heh...heh heh... You seem ready to burst into tears. I'd...fetch you a handkerchief, but...
There may be hope for Coldhearth yet if that Baut fellow can really persuade the folks in Ala Ghiri to help with plantin' our dates. If only Erart could be here to see the palms grow...
I take it now you see why I've been tryin' to keep this quiet? One misstep and there'll be blood in the streets for sure. I'm countin' on you to help bring him in.
Thanks again for your help. Baut's been surprisingly cooperative. In fact, my superiors are saying he may be pardoned.
Good seein' you,  . If you're lookin' for Baut, he's still up at Coldhearth helpin' with the crops.
When those dates get to growin', we can finally get to replenishin' our stores of arak. I've worked up a thirst just thinkin' about it.
Taking Velodyna will be the first significant step toward wresting Ala Mhigo from the Empire's grasp─but make no mistake: there will be many more such steps, each one taken at a cost.
Lord Hien saw fit to pardon me and my men for our crimes, and bade us return with him to Doma to help our countrymen rebuild.
Alas, there are other Lupin still bound by imperial chains to serve. Still others have turned to banditry, the wretched fools. It is enough to make me long for my brother's aid...
If this sodding leg of mine was any good, I'd...
Kami take me, I never believed this day would come! I'm sorry I doubted you before, my friend.
It's you! The womanman who came to set us free. Of course. You must have had a hand in this. My thanks to you.

Enjoying the festivities, I trust? Indeed, it is a time of celebration, but also a time of reflection. The Rising marks the anniversary of the realm's rebirth, and the selfless sacrifices of those who made it possible.
Please do partake in the revelry, and always remember: to ensure a bright future, we must never forget the past.
Thank you again for your help. Even with the bugs vanquished, I would find no joy in our celebration had it cost the wandering minstrel his life.
But let us not worry ourselves with things that will never be. Please do partake in the revelry, and always remember: to ensure a bright future, we must never forget the past.

Have you heard? They're selling all manner of commemorative goods in Ul'dah to celebrate the Rising. Fireworks, furniture, orchestrion rolls, you name it. If I were you, I'd go and have a look before their stocks are gone.
The surest way to hasten our progress is to improve our fare. Feed a man the same bland gruel weeks on end and see what you get!
Me? I've come on behalf of the House of Splendors. Got an assortment of uncanny knickknacks, as it happens. If you've got what I need, we could make ourselves a trade?
Do you seek passage to the Prima Vista?
No one goes in without the commander's permission.
The Resonatorium is a restricted area. I can't let you in without the proper authorization.
There's a hundred and one things to do, but I'll see the Saltery running again─you mark my words!
We've gone ahead and set up patrols like we talked about. Thanks to your advice, we shouldn't have any trouble keeping the area safe for the Saltery workers.
My thanks for your help.
I still have much to learn.
If not for you, the vault would be barren. <sigh> Perhaps Tsukumo was wrong to choose me...

The Divine Circle is engrossed in other work at present. Even with our combined strength, though, I fear we're still no match for the Red. We will require aid from all of Tamamizu if we're to succeed.
Whether it be scouring the ocean floor or bartering in the markets of Kugane, there are myriad ways to obtain treasure for the vault.
Kabuto is much too concerned with measuring himself against you. I pray he comes to understand this is not a competition, lest he lose sight of our goal.
I apologize for Kabuto's behavior earlier. It would appear he still has much to learn about what it means to work as a team.

For a time I think everyone feared that peace would not last, but there is no denying it now. The reconstruction has begun in earnest. Nevertheless, we must not neglect the simple pleasures in life, else why bother carrying on living at all?
I realize now we're only as strong as we are united. What a fool I've been, thinking I could support the Blue on my own. If only I had come to understand sooner.
Even if we don't always see eye to eye, I think of Tsukumo, and remember there is nothing we can't resolve with discussion.
Tsukumo granted me a great blessing in the Divine Circle. The bonds between us have never been stronger, and I will do all I can to honor and protect them in his memory.
I was all puffed up with pride when they chose me to speak for the Ala Mhigan Quarter─I sure didn't expect to be fleeing for my life!
...And, aye, I saw what Fordola did for us. She ain't forgiven─not by a damn sight─but we've better things to do than spill new blood for old wrongs.
! What brings you to Doma, my friend? I'd heard that the aftermath of Ala Mhigo's liberation brought its own trials, but can I assume the worst of it is over for the moment?
I know firsthand how difficult rebuilding a nation can be... After attending the kami know how many councils, I almost yearn for the simplicity of battles where one knows exactly where one stands.

We must, however, be thankful for the agony of choice─it is the undeniable proof of our freedom. Pray send Lyse my regards. I hope we soon find our present struggles relegated to amusing stories to share over a cup of wine!

Bandits have been attacking our workers, seeking to steal the materials we use to rebuild. I am most pained to see Lupin amongst their dishonorable ranks, slavering and snarling as if they were no more than common beasts.
Greetings,  ! As you can see, there is yet much to be done before we can fully erase the scars of war from the fair face of Doma.
I would have our people wielding tools rather than weapons, but we must also nurture the strength to protect our hard-won freedom. 'Tis a matter that I must discuss at length with Lord Hien...

We've cleared the streets of rubble for the most part, but...well, just look for yourself. I don't care how ramshackle it is─I need my smithy back! Too much time wasted coming back and forth from Kusakari. Too much!
We need to break up this fallen masonry and cart it away before we can think about building. It took some work, but the main thoroughfares are mostly free of debris now.
All are free to travel in and out of the enclave. Do you seek passage?
Repairing our homes is tiring work, but the exhaustion is accompanied by a great deal of satisfaction. Yes, indeed.
Is the conflict in Ala Mhigo nearly over? Do you think my conscripted brothers will be able to come home soon, as Hakuro's soldiers have?
Phew. These big stones are why the word “backbreaking” was invented, but you'll see─we'll have this area all cleaned up soon enough!
Did you notice how some of the buildings were left untouched? Like that damnable tower on the docks, or the mansion where the overseer lived?
Say what you will about the imperials, but they are nothing if not practical...

I must designate a priority for each structure, ensure that the necessary materials are delivered to the correct site, gather competent workers and see that they are properly fed, and then there's the─
Ah! How can one person keep track of so many details!? I shall have to find myself an assistant!
I find it reassuring to watch the children at their games─even with their homes in ruins, they still find ways to play. If only we all had such resilience.
One wrong step, and I would've lost my will to that fiend for the rest of my days. 'Tis a sobering thought...
We encountered our fair share of enthralled outside the palace. Enough to delay us from lending you a timely hand, I'm afraid...
I think I shall make a habit of checking for primal influence before our meetings from now on.
That was unlike any battle I've ever seen. I'm not entirely sure how I survived it, to be honest.
Lyse is certainly living up to her own ideal. Not every commander would choose to enlist a former enemy's aid in battle.
Kweh, kweh!
I have some of our best people deciphering the tomestone we retrieved from Omega's control room─you can browse their latest results on the terminal over there.

Rowena charged a pretty pile of gil to loan us a scholar to handle the translations, but I think I can chalk that up to “project expenses.” If that knowledge allows you even the slightest advantage, then no cost is too great...
Pray do not concern yourself with me, my friend! Should I chance upon the fiend, I shall cry “Wolf Burglar!” at the top of my lungs!
Would you look at these pretty houses! I mean, they could use a little work, but they've all got potential!
He will not escape. Not this time...I hope.
It'll be nice to have some Resistance lads and lasses around to watch over us. No one wants to worry about being dragged into the loch while you're just trying to get an honest day's work done.
Aye, the gate at the top of these stairs leads into the palace. Nay, I can't let you in without the proper say-so.
To commemorate the gathering of Ala Mhigo's envoys, they've decided to open the rooftop gardens to everyone in the city. Would you like to take a look?
Psst! Is it true you are taking part in expeditions into the Empty?
Fear not, Lewrey has made me swear not to tell another soul! Just know that you have the full support of the Settlement council. If there is anything you need, say the word!
Come to check on me, have you? Well, thanks to the excellent care I've received, I seem to be on the mend.
Not that that's stopped Alphinaud from insisting I continue my convalescence. I swear he decides to act the part of a concerned big brother at the most inconvenient of times...
It seems I'll be serving as the contact between Ala Mhigo and the Scions for the time being. Naturally, my duties will also include spying on beastman strongholds.
Now that freedom is won, we'd be fools to let it slip through our fingers. Though mayhap not on the front lines, I will lend what support I can to our Ala Mhigan brothers and sisters.
The kami has spoken,  . It falls to us to see the vault is filled to bursting with resplendent treasures.
Since beginning trade with the Namazu, opportunities to barter for goods have led us all across Othard. Truly, your meeting with their people was a blessing.

We must do our due diligence if we are to maintain good relations with the Qestir. Trading with them has taught us to be less reliant on our words as well, a valuable skill when dealing not only with the Qestir, but all the Xaela in Reunion.
What good fortune that Kabuto would be friends with a smith of the forge in Kugane? We are certain to have need of their services before facing the Red.
Few, if any of us, will cross blades with them, mind you, but I plan to do all I can to see we are duly prepared.
We've cut off the head of the snake, but it is only a matter of time before another grows in its place. Until then, Hirumaki's absence should deter the Red from interfering with our work.
The vault is a glorious sight, isn't it? It would likely still be empty if not for your efforts.
I cannot recall the kami Kabuto spoke of, but the blessing of your friendship to the Blue is undeniable.
Kabuto has never been one to work with others, but please, do what you can for him.
Have you heard? Kabuto has been helping tend to the rays! I would never have believed it had I not seen it with my own eyes.
If there was any doubt he was blessed by a kami, it's been washed away by the tide.
Our wares are mostly what we find or goods we've received but have no need for. Have a look and see if there's anything you need.

If you're interested in owning a striped ray, you're in luck. I've spoken with Makura and Takotsubo, and they've given me leave to sell them to adventurers such as yourself who've made considerable contributions to the Blue.
Ladies and gentlemen, young and old! Once more the Songbirds will grace the stages of Ul'dah in celebration of Little Ladies' Day.
Indeed, it shall be a performance for the ages, one wherein you will have the opportunity to take part. If you would join in the revelry, pray make for Ul'dah with all haste.

The Crystal Exarch has tasked me with exploring the practical applications of materia, a most wondrous substance indeed. I fear, however, that there is little I can offer to those who do not possess a fundamental knowledge of the subject.

The Crystal Exarch has tasked me with exploring the practical applications of materia. I take it that you, too, have a passing familiarity in such matters? In that case, I would be more than happy to share with you what I know.
Looking to exchange materia, are you? Then you have most certainly come to the right place!
Once again, the Starlight Celebration is bringing joy to children far and wide. We've been so busy that we'd be glad for any help you might offer!
So, you've spoken with Baenfaeld? It's a crying shame what happened in Bentbranch, it really is. Please, help him bring cheer to those dear little children!
Baenfaeld tells me you were instrumental in recovering the decorations. We are eternally grateful!
When I look at you, I cannot help but recall the Ishgardian knights from the tale of the first Starlight Celebration. Such selflessness and generosity─ You truly are an example to us all!
Welcome to Garik! Is that the jingling of coins I hear coming from your pocket?
Greetings, good madamsir. I am the inoshishi bugyo, come with a delegation from the Far East on a mission to deepen the bonds of friendship with the people of Eorzea.

It is my honor and privilege to share our Heavensturn customs in this, the year of the boar. To mark this momentous occasion, I will be serving traditional sweets to the good people here in Limsa Lominsa. If you would care to sample a taste of the Far East, you need only come and join the celebration.
Ah, come to join the celebration, have you? With the neko bugyo gone, this year's Heavensturn has been a smashing success.
Though I cannot help but wonder if he truly intends to return... In any case, I will personally see to it the next year's bugyo is prepared. On that, you have my word.
<grunt>
Oink, oink!
I'm a personal assistant of Master Wiscard hisself. Don't know the big man? Then, all the 'stounding wares I have─you don't know these either. Farewell!
You know Master Wiscard? Why didn't you say so! What can I get you?
I live to see my clients dressed with style and finesse. Only those I deem suitable are permitted to browse my stock.
It seems you too appreciate the importance of outward appearances. Pray, view my wares.
We'll be watching the Qalyana even more closely now, ready to jump if they try summoning Lakshmi again.
Papalymo taught me a lot about the dangers of being enthralled, and I'll be passing on that advice to our fighters. Can't be too careful when there's a primal involved.
The sultana's relocation project appears to be proceeding as planned.
With the mad king's gold at our disposal, we've already begun preparing the Saltery to accommodate the returning refugees. At this pace, Ala Mhigo will be thriving again in no time!

I know I'm not the best fighter, but that battle against Lakshmi brought home how badly I need to train. I'll be putting myself at the mercy of J'moldva and V'mah until I feel ready to face a primal on my own!
They've been quiet since their treachery in the throne room, but the Qalyana are a problem we'll need to solve at some point...
Lyse took on a great deal of responsibility with very little warning─I expect it's a considerable relief to know that Raubahn is in Ala Mhigo to stay.
Not once, but twice now have you besssted the Qalyana's mockery of our goddess.
Our wayward sssisters would have rent this land asssunder with their misssplaced faith, and on behalf of the Ananta I both thank you and beg your forgiveness.
You saved my life,  , and I welcome you without hesitation. I doubt I could ever say the same for the Butcher, though, no matter how heroic her deeds...
Greetings, my friend. Following the Qalyana's treachery, we have been scrutinizing their movements even more closely than usual.
I would not be known as the nunh who allowed the Ananta's goddess to make slaves of his people.
! Welcome, welcome! I hear your negotiations with our chairman went splendidly!
Offering up the Saltery as a potential investment was a master stroke, I must say. Like many a gourmand, the way to Lolorito's purse is through his stomach! Ahahaha!
Alphinaud has been sending me detailed reports on the happenings in Ala Mhigo. The war is over, but there are still a few battles left to be fought, eh?
Hoary Boulder and the others are off visiting the more troublesome beast tribes. It seems that business with Sri Lakshmi inspired an unscheduled scouting expedition...
We've had a few setbacks this Hatchingtide, but you needn't let that stop you from enjoying the festivities!
Traveling troubadour and master minstrel, at your service! I shall be stopping here in Gridania for a time, and keeping my senses open to new inspiration.
How fare you in your impromptu performances? Mayhap one day we could play a duet together...
I know Grandfather and Homei have yet to discuss it, but with the liberation of Doma, it is surely only a matter of time before the refugees decide to return to the Far East, no?

Don't you worry about ol' Riol─let him worry about you. I'm keepin' my ears to the ground, havin' 'em listen for anythin' an' everythin' what might cause us trouble. I'll not suffer any more knives in the dark. Save ours, that is.
Garnering support from the others to face the Red will prove difficult, more so for one of Kabuto's reticent disposition. May the kami grant him strength.
Kabuto's command of the Blue on the Isle of Zekki was above and beyond my wildest expectations. Not only that─he was able to defeat their general. The kami smile upon us.
Thanks to you and the tsukumogami, Kabuto has become an exemplary leader for the Divine Circle. I confess I had my doubts at first, but he has proven himself quite capable.
Leave the underlings to me. You have a primal to fight!
Head outside to prepare?
The troupe's nefarious plan to sow terror with their costumes seems to have spiraled out of control, leaving them with little time to engage in other mischief. And the manor is of no moment.
Nevertheless, I will remain vigilant, for evil never sleeps! And if it does, it sleeps in shifts!
Hmm... Surely someone will come along...someone both willing and able to help...
In order to undertake the quest “An Othardian Wolfman in Gridania,” you must first complete the quest “It's Probably Pirates.”
We were visited by a refugee just the other day. He said he had come to share the news of his impending move to the Saltery.

It would seem that a companion─one who did not survive their flight across the badlands all those years ago─is buried here in the lichyard... I feel I was afforded a glimpse of the bittersweet joy that many an Ala Mhigan must surely now endure.
...He truly has no idea what those fiends are really about, does he? Well, the least we can do is try to keep him from getting into even more trouble, for his sake and for ours.
With Lord Hien's return, I can rest easy knowing that Doma is in good hands.
...Still, after hearing the tales of Ala Mhigo's restoration, I am tempted to rush home and put these old bones to work alongside my countrymen.

It seems an age now since we first imposed upon your kindness. We have strived to make ourselves useful here whilst our homeland lay in turmoil, but the time has come where we must choose our path forward...
I cannot return to Doma with head held high until our debt to you has been repaid. Honor demands that I stand ready to perform any task you may require of me. And so I train!
Ah, how I miss the inexhaustible font of Lyse's energy. The Rising Stones is a sadder place for her absence...
Yet I cannot begrudge her the vital duty she performs in the name of her homeland. Indeed, she sets a shining example for the rest of us to follow!
Ah,  . Is there no way we can arrange for Homei and his kin to return to Doma? I know he will not ask it for himself, but it's plain to see where his heart yearns to be.
I'm bound for Sakazuki. For a few coins, you can come too. Interested?
I'm bound for Sakazuki. For a few coins─ Eh? You haven't even got that much? Never mind.
Got a mind to head to Onokoro? I'll take you there, for a pittance. You have my word that no harm will come to you...
Got a mind to head to Onokoro? I'll take you there, for a pittance...or would, if that weren't beyond your humble means.
Clean as a baby's behind, it is! But when we get to work, it will be anything but, heh heh! Day and night, day and night I will soon be laboring. Far too much to be done!
If you need someone to lift a sledge, I'm your man, but if the hammer in question is a fair bit smaller, you'd be better served by another. Either way, I'm taking a rest.
The others saw fit to entrust this site to me, and I will not let them down.
Have you heard aught of the other Lupin conscripts in Eorzea? Surely there is no reason why they would not have left by now, but the lack of news is concerning...

I oversee the distribution of materials and the delegation of various essential tasks. It is a great responsibility that the elders have given me, and I shall prove to them and everyone else that I am up to the challenge!
Woodworking, now this is more like it! Far less exhausting, and it provides greater opportunities to express myself artistically. Why, it's so engrossing I almost forgot how hungry I am...
Curious about where these doors lead? Nowhere particularly interesting, really. We had to demolish a number of unsafe structures, and have yet to build anything in their place.

You could say we bid farewell to those lingering remnants of a tragic past. An ending to mark a new beginning, so to speak.
...Hmm? Did I say something odd?
Every stone is in its place once more. Parents need not fear for their children tripping over debris as they run. Still, I would rather they played on softer grounds...
If necessary, we will evacuate the civilians into the mountains.
, should you not be with Lord Hien at Castrum Fluminis?
Doma has but regained her freedom. We will not give it up again so soon. Whatever should be the Empire's intent, I stand ready to protect the people with my life.
The residents took the news of the imperial delegation well enough. It should be business as usual.
So it's to be a peace negotiation. I am curious to see what the ambassador brings to the discussion table.
Thanks to Master Alphinaud and Mistress Alisaie's assurances, the people are reacting calmly to imperial presence.
We're finally back to working in earnest. We've even got merchants passing through from time to time. Things are finally turning around for the Saltery.
As the Saltery prospers, so too will Ala Mhigo. All the more reason we have to keep the area safe for the workers.
With production back on track, the Saltery is bustling in a way I've not seen in years. You've given us the tools to build a future for ourselves as well as for Ala Mhigo!
It's all coming together. With the return of our brothers and sisters, we've workers to spare─not that I'm shirking my patrol duties, you understand!
You stand before the Kienkan, residence of Lord Hien.
Between my findings here in Kugane and Riol's in Eorzea, I'm quite certain we can learn all there is to know of the growing divisions within the Empire.
Whatever Asahi is planning, we cannot let him have his way. After all Lord Hien has done, the Empire cannot be suffered to hinder Doma's restoration.
<sigh> Just when I thought Alphinaud had grown more dependable... Ack, but complaining about it won't bring back the coin. I must think of ways to recoup our funds.
I will replenish our coffers, you wait and see. If all goes as planned, we will recoup the cost of Gosetsu's blade ten times over!
I hope Soroban is doing all right. I may have to pay him a visit to make sure he isn't growing lax in his training...
The Empire's recent movement presents an opportunity for profit. You may leave it to me to sniff it out!
More often than not, it seems opportunity is wont to come knocking when the Scions are about. So long as you and yours remain here in Kugane, I'm certain a profitable venture will present itself.
In my mind, Yotsuyu is deserving of only one fate─memory loss be damned. And if you don't have the stones for it, we would be happy to take on the burden. It'll be over nice and swift.
To think that that she-devil yet lives to breathe Doman air... No good can come of this, mark my words.
Forgive me, but if you wish to peruse those particular tomes, I must ask that you first speak with Guiding Star. You can find him over yonder, with Talan.
Afraid I can't oblige you just yet. There's a fellow in Revenant's Toll you'll need to see first─Guiding Star, I believe is his name?
Those tomes are reserved for only the most skilled individuals. You will need to go and see Guiding Star in Revenant's Toll before I can show them to you.
Haven't got anything for ye, friend. Not until I hear ye've spoken with Guiding Star in Revenant's Toll.
Let's not put the cart before the chocobo. You need to go and see Guiding Star in Revenant's Toll before I can sell you any of those tomes.
A thousand pardons, my friend, but those tomes can only be purchased by a select few that have received the approval of Guiding Star in Revenant's Toll.
If you're an artisan with an interest in certain esoteric tomes, you would be well served by paying a visit to Guiding Star in Revenant's Toll.
In the market for master crafting tomes? Well enough, Eorzean, but you'll need to see a man in your homeland first─one Guiding Star in Revenant's Toll.

Tell me, is Alphinaud doing alright? Before leaving to Kugane, he insisted I accompany him to Loch Seld to oversee his swimming practice. The waters there are so rich with salt a boulder is like to float in them. The open sea, however, is another matter. I pray he doesn't do anything foolish.
I never realized Raubahn was so affluent in matters of money and politics, though in hindsight it should have been obvious. He was a member of the Syndicate, after all.
His help has been invaluable, but I cannot depend on him forever. I have to be ready to stand on my own, even if I have to study... So long as the books aren't too large, of course.
We've got a lot of work to do before Mother sheds her ssskin!
With the help of the griffin riders, we'll be able to patrol much farther afield.
When Gales is working, he's like a man possessed!
I quite like having M'zhet around. No matter how much of a messs I make of things, I can rely on him to make me look good by comparissson!
I thought the other Gatekeepers would be against taking in the Qalyana ssseparatists, but our new recruits were given a surprisingly warm welcome.
The Gatekeepers have come a long way, but as J'olhmyn sssays, “It's too early to rest on our laurels!”
Keeping Alpa out of trouble seemed like a daunting task at first. Now that you're here, I can breathe a little more easily...
The “down with the castellum” mob came to cause a fuss, but they soon shut their traps when they saw the griffin statues!
With Alpa as captain, we had enough strangeness to deal with already. Now that we've got this Gales bloke, it looks like things'll get even weirder around here...
I gave M'zhet quite a pummeling but it didn't seem to do him any lasting damage. I guess all the beatings he's received over the years have toughened him up.
Despite starting with just a handful of troops, the Gatekeepers have become a force to be reckoned with!

I'm happy that Alpa can stand on her own two feet─figuratively speaking of course! Although my work as her mentor is done, I'll be carrying on as a member of the Gatekeepers. What can I say? I like it here!
I am resssponsssible for asssigning tasks to adventurers. I can give you work should you wish to aid our cause.

I cannot help but envy the ssstriders who sssoar through the ssskies on the backs of griffins. Unfortunately, it ssseems that griffins have a natural aversion to the Ananta and will not allow us to ride them.
I never knew that ssstriders are unable to sssleep coiled up like Ananta.
It must be terribly inconvenient having sssuch a rigid body. You always look ssso uncomfortable!
That man's bizarre behavior was caused by lovesssickness?
Although we Ananta are aware of the concept of romantic love, we have no need for it. Compared to familial love, it ssseems frivolous and unnecesssary.

The new Qalyana recruits have already settled in well and their commitment to the cause is beyond question. We still have plenty of work to offer adventurers though, ssso let me know if you wish to help.
We Vira have watched over Alpa sssince she came into this world. It brings us great joy to sssee that she has grown into a ssstrong and dependable leader.
As one of her most loyal friends and a sssteadfast comrade to the Gatekeepers, you have our deepest gratitude.
Full glad am I that us griffin riders can help keep the Velodyna region safe. It's not the easiest place to patrol on foot, so I'm sure we can make a difference.
That Alpa─she's quite the leader, wouldn't you say? I get the impression those new Qalyana recruits would lay down their lives for her.
The Gatekeepers can rely on us griffin riders to be their “eyes in the sky”! We're also the first to get stuck in when fighting breaks out.
What do you think of our marids? In times of peace, their ssstrength makes light of the most demanding physical work. But in times of war, a rampaging marid is unssstoppable.
We Ananta ride marids by twisssting our tails around their trunks. I always find it ssstrange to see you ssstriders riding on their backsss.
Sometimes I get so engrossed in my work that I forget myself and say things I later regret... I'll try to exercise more restraint from now on.
Now that we have a garrison for the new Qalyana members, I've had the chance to see even more examples of Ananta culture. It has been quite the learning experience!
Alpa and the others don't seem to mind my eccentricities at all. I suppose it takes more than a little shouting and fist-waving to scare these soldier types!
We have a ssselection of wares for friends of the Gatekeepers. Feel free to peruse them at your leisure.
Would you like to be the proud owner of a mighty marid?
Your deeds in ssservice of the Gatekeepers have earned you the recognition of the marid handlers. They have granted you the right to keep one of your own.
These statues look just like the real thing─apart from being all golden and shiny, of course.
Everyone that's passed through these gates has been impressed by the statues, especially the Ala Mhigans. Their faces light up when they see them!
Thisss is the garrissson of the Ananta members of the Gatekeepers. It is the perfect place to ressst after a day of patrolling.
I can ssscarcely believe the day has come that Vira and Qalyana can live and work together. Captain Alpa has ushered in a new era.
We have much to learn from the ssstrider chirurgeons. They can even treat afflictions that we Ananta thought to be incurable.
On the other hand, Ananta medicine relies sssolely on local ingredients, so it's useful when there's no time to get supplies imported from other lands.
More and more people passs through here every day, many of whom have injuries and afflictions which require treatment. Even with our combined efforts, it is a ssstruggle to keep up.
Providing sssuccor for those in need is a worthwhile cause, but I do wish our patients would take better care of themssselves!
These rooms have been set assside for those passsing through the castellum. The sssoldiers stay in the garrison, while adventurers are asked to make their own arrangements.
Gyr Abania is prossspering now that the Garleans have gone. We have ssseen a dramatic increase in merchants crosssing the Velodyna, bringing goods from lands afar.
I can't help but feel envious of Alpa. She already has the respect of her whole tribe, including the broodmother!
I can't afford to waste any more time. My legend begins right here, right now!
Working with Alpa, I've realized that if I were serpent marshal, I wouldn't have to take part in any fighting.
All I have to do is become more qualified than Serpent Marshal Brookstone...which is a fair bit easier said than done, I suppose...
Heading towards Virdjala, are you?
Another mission fraught with danger, yet here I am still... Quiet moments such as this, spent in carefree conversation with comrades, I have grown to cherish most.
As you may have heard, we recently stepped up our surveillance of the beast tribes. My brother and I, we were out scouting near Zahar'ak when we were ambushed by an Amalj'aa.
But if our assailant was quick as a coeurl, Hoary was a lightning bolt. In one fluid motion, he parried the blow and ended the encounter with a sublime shield bash. 'Tis a sight I shan't soon forget!
Hoary returns from every mission a finer warrior than when he set out. I must work harder if I am to keep up.
Those of us who were afield have finally returned. Full glad am I to have everyone back─the place had been too quiet.
(I know I need to give Isildaure my undivided attention, but these waves of brotherly love make my mind drift to naughty places... Focus, Aenor! Focus!)
(I hope Isildaure can find someone to keep him company. With our missions, we can never linger very long.)
Seeing Homei going about his duties with a smile lifts my heart even as it brings a tear to my eye. Glad though I am for his nation's liberation, I shall be saddened to see him go.
I appreciate the young ones' concern, but as Isildaure has taught me, age is but a barrier in one's mind. These old bones can still put in a good day's work, and the spirit is amply willing besides!
Revenant's Toll has grown tremendously. As we move forward, instead of breaking new ground, perhaps it is time to focus on refining that which already stands.
Every time word reaches us of developments in Doma, we are stirred to greater effort. Our countrymen work tirelessly to rebuild our homeland, and in applying ourselves here, we join them in spirit.
Oh,  , what a pleasant surprise! Whatever business brings you here, I pray it will keep you a while. Do make yourself comfortable.
The Domans have as much claim to Revenant's Toll as you and me. They're family. Thank the gods I made it back in time to see them off.
Will Isildaure be all right without Homei? They're practically inseparable these days, and I don't think he has many other friends...
It is for the best. It is. It is their past and their future. Their home. And I...I could not be happier for them...
You needn't worry for my grandfather. If he should grow lonely and start to long for Homei's company, he will purchase passage on the next ship bound for the Far East. I couldn't stop him if I tried!
I have been charged with preparing food for the Gatekeepers, though I've yet to find aught that suits the tassstes of striders.
My cooking ssskills only continue to grow here at Castellum Velodyna, and the work has actually grown to be enjoyable.
It has also grown easier, thanksss to the newly furnished kitchen here. Soon even the ssstriders will salivate at the sight of my cooking.
I'm convinced now that cooking is my passion. To see the look of sssatisfaction on travelers' faces after sampling my cooking... I never knew such joy exisssted.
And never would have had I not joined the Gatekeepers. Thanksss to Alpa's vision, and your dedication to our cause, I have found my true calling. Thank you.
Though we drove the Garleans out, 'twould be foolish to expect that they will give up so readily. We must redouble our vigilance and work closely with our comrades at the enclave.
I heard the Empire has proposed an exchange of prisoners. To speak plain, I am quite skeptical of their intentions. Still, I hope the arrangement goes as planned.
Fear not, my ladylord. Should Yotsuyu attempt to escape, these finely honed muscles will stop her dead in her tracks.
The Empire promises peace with Doma, but I will not let down my guard, nor will I slacken my training. Come what may, I will be ready.
Lord Hien bade us keep Yotsuyu's presence the strictest secret. Should even the whisper of a rumor reach the people's ears, all hells would break loose.
If our brothers and sisters are returned to us, mayhap we can at last restore Monzen to its former glory. Of course, we would first need to do away with my creations still roaming the ruins there.
That we should reclaim our freedom only to be afflicted with that woman...
Though I despise the thought of bargaining with the Empire, I agree with Lord Hien's decision. If there is even the faintest chance our people can be returned to us, we must try.
Doma has only begun to rebuild. I can only pray that we do not suffer another war.

Peace with the Empire could mean the beginning of open trade with Doma, and more supplies to bolster the rebuilding effort. Yet I cannot help but wonder what our conscripted brethren would think of us working with imperials.
There will come a time when we will call upon you again, but not yet. For now, I advise you to rest and regain your strength.
The boundless rage which once threatened to consume me has abated. This I owe to you, brave warrior.
(This...this began with a petition seeking your aid, not mine...)
If you chance to meet Tamamo Gozen, I pray you tell her that we all miss her dearly.
I'm Nue. If you ever need someone to call lightning down upon your foes and whatnot, I'm your auspice.

'Course, some faerie tales would have you believe I'm something altogether different. A monkey's face, a lion's legs, a snake for a tail─ridiculous, am I right? Not as bad as that horse with the head and body of a rabbit, to be fair, but still...
Inugami is my name. Men speak it in hushed tones, mistakenly believing me to be a vengeful spirit that murders indiscriminately.
There was a time when I killed men by the hundreds, but that was in retribution for the countless creatures they themselves mercilessly slaughtered. It was most deliberate.
You will go no further. The reason should be plain─beyond lies the prison of Koryu. Were you to damage the wards, he would break free, and all would fall to ruin.
Headed to the surface? Follow me!
Alphinaud's been keeping a very careful count of his coins lately. I doubt he'd ask for a sip of water without asking the price first! Hee hee hee!
Headed for the temple or just taking in the wonderful smoky air?
Oh my, yes, I remember those two. The young girl scoffing down dango and the grizzled samurai. I can only tell you what I've heard, but it seems they're seeking a boat to cross the Ruby Sea.
Thank you again for saving me and Azami from the Kojin.
Though to be honest, I was terrified when that imperial first arrived. I thought he'd come to finish what the Kojin had started.
Isse invited you all to visit, but I was hoping we could go to the enclave. I'd very much like to see Lady Yugiri again.
Until we know what Asahi is after, we can but wait and prepare for the exchange of prisoners.
Have you come on business? Or perhaps to observe our work in rebuilding the enclave? Feel free to look around. The people would be glad for your presence.
If you are looking for Gosetsu, he is with Yotsuyu, keeping close watch of her. Yes, quite close indeed...
We have spared no effort to increase the guard at every settlement here in Yanxia. The Red Kojin will trouble us no more. On that, you have my word.
Me? I'm an engineer, here to assist with the development of the Saltery. And yes, I suppose building a crane or two here would be easier than hauling it up the steps...
One shouldn't rely overmuch on one's tools. It's like they say: to a man with a crane, everything looks like─ Wait, that's not right...
Everything's moving much faster with the help of these cranes. It's like they say: give a man a winch, and he'll eat for the rest of his─ Wait, that came out wrong...
This year's Little Ladies' Day celebration is well underway. I certainly hope you will find time to take part in the festivities.
Triple Triad? The Western game, yes? I learned the basics from a traveling merchant long ago. If you would like to play a game, I have my own cards!
Forgive me, but I cannot indulge in games when I am this hungry. It is enough to impede my concentration...
Well, would you look at that! I win! This is more fun than I remember. I ought to try and teach the others how to play again.
I blame this empty belly of mine. Hunger is a terrible distraction. You would not expect a soldier to fight in such a condition, would you?
It would seem we are more evenly matched than I thought. Perchance you are hungry too?

I wouldn't say no to a game or two. Although I must warn you: I'm known as one of the best in the Confederacy.
Having spent longer than I care to think about surveying the horizon, my eyes need a rest. If it's a game of cards you're after, I suggest asking someone else.
You're not the first to lose to me, and you won't be the last. Normally, I'd celebrate with a few swigs of something strong, but I'll need a clear head when I'm back on duty.
You certainly know how to play, unlike most of the drunkards and swindlers around here. I've no qualms about taking their coin, but they don't offer much in terms of practice.
While a draw seems like a fair result, it's not in a pirate's nature to leave things unsettled. I trust you'll oblige me another game?
I would be delighted for the chance to hone my skills. Rounds of Triple Triad often serve as a precursor to negotiations with our Eorzean clients, so I am no stranger to the game.
I'm dreadfully sorry, but as you can see, I'm rather busy.
Try not to be disheartened. I daresay I'm a cut above the amateurs you're used to playing.
That was somewhat unexpected. I admit that I will often intentionally lose to clients to keep them...malleable. However, a client you are not, and your win was entirely deserved.
A draw─in which we are both spared the bitter sting of defeat, yet deprived the sweet satisfaction of victory. It would be a shame for our contest to end so inconclusively. Care for another round?
Triple Triad? Little do you know I used to be a regular at the Saucer! I've got time to spare, so let's have ourselves a game or three.
Looks like it's my round! Gods, I needed that. Been drowning in work ever since I got here, let me tell you.
Blast. I'm too out of practice. Tried playing a couple of the folks here, but I wasn't feeling it. Best to keep business and pleasure separate, you know?
Pushed me to the limit, you did. You're a good opponent. If you ever want to have another go, let me know!
I have the pleasure of selling myriad fashion supplies, but I am afraid I can offer them only to those who take part in the Fashion Report. My sincerest apologies.
All of the items in stock come highly recommended. Pray browse to your heart's content.
I never would have dreamed that Jihli was the egg thief all along!
But I forgive her the deception. After all, if she hadn't followed her vision, imagine all the wondrous encounters that never would have taken place!
! It's so good to see you. As you can see, this year's Little Ladies' Day celebration is off to a smashing start. I trust you will find time to take part in our merrymaking, yes?
The Songbirds' performance was simply wonderful wasn't it? Well, if you should have the time to attend their show again, they have performances scheduled until the very end of the festival.
Giff has ssset aside one of his griffins for you to keep as your own. A beautiful, white true griffin, at that.
He cares for those beasssts as though they were his children, ssso you should consssider it a great honor. I trussst you will take good care of it.
I wish I could join the Doman Adventurers' Guild and go on special adventures and wear special hats!
Valentione's Day is upon us once more, and I, Lisette de Valentione, have come to fill hearts the realm over with the warmth of love, passionate and pure!
Come one, come all─but ideally, come in pairs─and partake of the revelry! Let your innermost feelings be known unto the object of your ardor and affection, and love shall surely bloom!
In order to undertake the quest “Lessons in Love,” you must first complete the quest “It's Probably Pirates.”
Ah, 'tis you, my dear adventurer! How are you liking this year's festivities? They shall continue on for a little while yet, so pray enjoy them while you still can.

Our retinue has made the journey from Ishgard, in the hope of helping the people of Eorzea express their deepest feelings, during this season of romance. We shall do our utmost to give succor to those troubled by matters of the heart.
Lest you wonder, Astrid and Lisette are in fact cousins, but they are so close as to be like true sisters.
Now, if only Astrid would come to accept me as a brother...or simply not despise me so. I know not what I have done to offend her...
G-Good people of Gridania! V-Valentione's Day is upon us once more! S-So embrace your feelings... Open your hearts... Something something true love...
(Gah, Fury take me, why am I so terrible at this?)

I can't thank you enough for helping to make the ceremony a rousing success. Please enjoy the festivities while they continue, and encourage your friends to─
...No, that won't do. Let's try that again.
Ahem! Love comes not to those who wait, but those who participate! So take part in the heartwarming fun of the Valentione's Day celebration, and seize love by the...by the...tail?
<sigh> This will take some getting used to...
You there! Would you like to know if you are meant for love? If so, you need but participate in the Valentione's Day festivities, and I shall reveal to you your fortune as it is writ in the cards.
Do riches lie in your future, or rags? By my esoteric powers I shall divine for you the answer. I ask only that you take part in the Valentione's Day celebration with your object of your adoration.
I shall test your compatibility with any adventurer who strikes your fancy. Simply join in the revelry of Valentione's Day, and I should be glad to offer you a reading!
The village has been abuzz with talk of Alpa's exploits. I will have to ensure these sssuccesses do not go to her head.
I've spoken with Raubahn, and we've decided to keep quiet about Zenos until we have undeniable proof. There's no sense in upsetting everyone if there's a chance we're wrong.
So the grave was empty. By Rhalgr... How many people did we lose bringing that bastard down─and now he might still be alive?
There's nothing like the thrill of the hunt to set one's heart to racing.
Yes, and you seem to have the gait of one familiar with the sport. But have you strength enough to be considered my rival? I'd very much like to find out.
, as I live and breathe! The hunters of Clan Centurio speak quite highly of you.
I can see there's much to be done if I'm to compete with a hunter of your renown.
Off on another hunt, are we? Be sure to leave a few marks for the rest of us.
The hunt is on, my friend, and that means work for me and my hammer.
My partner here's mainly in for the bounty, but he never fails to bring me back something for the forge. If you ever have something what needs smithing, maybe I can lend you a hand as well.
Ah,  . Good to see you. You've any more scales for me?
Lyse told me about Alphinaud's little jaunt into the Empire. I can't believe he left without telling me─I've half a mind to dunk him in the lake when he gets back!

As promised, the conscripts without families have found a home with the Confederacy. I almost wish we had thought to poach imperial soldiers earlier─there is an undeniable strength and confidence to those who survive the front lines of the Empire's wars.
So the witch is dead, is she? I'd celebrate more were it not for the hurt I saw in the old samurai's eyes. Never have I seen a man more broken...

Soroban was terrifying! I mean, who could have predicted he had the potential to become a rampaging auspice of death and destruction? Anyone's Carbuncle would've run. Anyone's. Even yours─and if you're about to tell me yours wouldn't, don't.!

There's still no word from Alphinaud.
<sigh> Patience has never been one of my virtues, but I suppose there is little else to do but wait...
You've heard naught from our intrepid Alphinaud? He travels under my protection as an emissary of Doma, and I would share any news of his journey.

In the meantime, you might enjoy seeing what the act of rescuing our conscripts has done for the enclave's restoration efforts. Their homecoming has been as an invigorating wind, and we return to our labors with renewed purpose.

Seeing these families celebrate the return of their loved ones... It has rekindled a yearning for my homeland I had thought long buried. But my duty is to Lord Hien─I swore allegiance to Doma, and it falls to me to fill the void left by Gosetsu's departure.
As a former soldier of the Empire, I have been chosen to oversee the handover of our imperial prisoners. Whilst I am so occupied, I must ask that you provide steadfast support for Lord Hien.
With the departure of the general, the defense of Doma rests in my hands.
And yet they do not tremble. The return of our conscripts has swelled our ranks to a most formidable number. Glad I am that I need not turn to my brother for reinforcements.
